"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681820","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-13","<p>There have been no significant restrictions on providing humanitarian assistance to Rohingya in camps in Rakhine State. These are outside the area affected by security operations since October 2016. Malnutrition rates in camps remain poor by international standards, with 8.6% of people suffering acute malnutrition according to the most recent survey. This is comparable to other areas in Burma. Mortality data is not systematically collected by international agencies providing support to the camps.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-02-13T15:45:57.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681820/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681820/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-31","Burma: Rohingya","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of deaths, illness and malnutrition in camps for the Rohingya in Rakhine State, Burma, as a result of restrictions on access to humanitarian assistance.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL5133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681821","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-09","<p>We will decide how best to respond to the findings of the pilot programmes on statutory notices once we have concluded consideration of those findings.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-02-09T16:51:22.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681821/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681821/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Local Government: Newspaper Press","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 23 January (HL4428), what is the timeframe for their decision on how to respond to the findings of the pilot programmes; and whether the response will be published.","true","Biography information for Lord Porter of Spalding",,"Lord Porter of Spalding","HL5134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681822","Home Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>We are currently developing the new Drug Strategy, working across government and with key partners. The new strategy will be published soon.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-07T16:28:59.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681822/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681822/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Drugs: Misuse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why publication of the new drugs strategy, which was expected to be in March 2016, has been delayed.","false","Biography information for Lord Ramsbotham",,"Lord Ramsbotham","HL5135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681823","Home Office","false","2017-02-14","<p>Policing is a devolved matter, and as such the level of policing required and costs incurred for specific events is a matter for the relevant Chief Constable and Police and Crime Commissioner. Police and Crime Commissioners can make an application for a Special Grant if they face significant and exceptional costs.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-14T12:00:57.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681823/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681823/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","State Visits: USA","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the cost to the UK of providing security for the visit of the US President to the UK; and which department or agency will be meeting those costs.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL5136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681824","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-08","<p>In 2015, approximately 11% of UK Official Development Assistance (ODA) was made up of core assessed contributions to the EU.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-02-08T17:44:33.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681824/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681824/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-31","EU Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proportion of UK official development assistance is spent through the EU.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681825","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-13","<p>DFID funding supports improved access to health care for refugees in Greece, according to need. We do not earmark funding for particular health services. Our support provides access to sexual and reproductive health services, including maternity services such as medical services for pregnant and breastfeeding women.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-02-13T15:50:26.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681825/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681825/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-31","Greece: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proportion of UK aid to refugees in Greece is earmarked for sexual and reproductive health, including access to hospital maternity services.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681826","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-13","<p>DFID supports access to sexual and reproductive health services for refugees in Greece. This includes provision of essential commodities, including family planning methods.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-02-13T16:09:17.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681826/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681826/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-31","Greece: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will support the procurement of essential sexual and reproductive health commodities, including modern family planning methods, for all refugees in Greece.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681827","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-13","<p>DFID supports safe accommodation spaces for unaccompanied asylum-seeking minors in Greece where children benefit from essential support. To date, we have supported more than 500 spaces.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-02-13T16:09:47.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681827/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681827/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-31","Greece: Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what support they are giving to unaccompanied asylum-seeking minors in Greece.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681828","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-13","<p>The UK provides funding for safe spaces for unaccompanied asylum-seeking minors in Greece. This includes support to the Faros-run shelter in Athens.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-02-13T15:50:40.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681828/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681828/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-31","Greece: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether  they give financial or other support to the Faros project in Greece which provides accommodation for young refugee boys who are at risk of sexual exploitation.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681829","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-13","<p>The full implications of the reinstated and expanded Mexico City policy are not yet clear but we are closely following developments. DFID will consider the implications with our offices, with UK civil society and with donors.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-02-13T15:40:31.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681829/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681829/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-31","Developing Countries: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will increase funding for abortion, contraception, and reproductive health information and services, in the light of the re-establishment of the global gag rule by President Trump.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681830","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-14","<p>As at 31 December 2016 there were 3,683 prisoners serving a sentence of Imprisonment for Public Protection (IPP). Of the 3,683 IPPs, 599 were pre-tariff and 3,081 were post-tariff. There are currently fewer than 3 IPP prisoners in prisons aged over 80 years old.</p><p> </p><p>We are working hard to reduce the backlog of parole hearings involving IPP prisoners. We have set up a new unit within the Ministry of Justice to tackle this issue and are working with the Parole Board to improve the efficiency of the process.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-14T15:51:08.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681830/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681830/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-31","Prison Sentences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many persons are presently serving sentences of imprisonment for public protection in England and Wales; and how many of them are more than 80 years of age.","false","Biography information for Lord Trefgarne",,"Lord Trefgarne","HL5143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681831","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-08","<p>At contract award in 2012, Royal Fleet Auxiliary (RFA) TIDESPRING was expected to enter service in October 2016.</p><p>In order to address emergent technical issues, the programme schedule was revised in 2016, and RFA TIDESPRING was accepted off-contract in January 2017. On current plans, we expect RFA TIDEPSRING to start UK customisation and capability assessment trials in the spring, before entering service with the RFA by the end of 2017.</p><p>We expect all four Maritime Afloat Reach and Sustainability (MARS) tankers to have entered service with the RFA by the end of 2018, as planned.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-08T16:20:16.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681831/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681831/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-31","RFA Tidespring","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the original planned date for acceptance into service of Royal Fleet Auxiliary Tidespring; and what is now the planned date for acceptance into service.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL5144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681832","Home Office","false","2017-02-16","<p>EU citizens and their family members have the right to enter, live and acquire permanent residence in other Member States when certain conditions are met, as set out in EU law. This includes a requirement to hold comprehensive sickness insurance where they have been exercising their Treaty rights as students and later rely on such periods to qualify for permanent residence.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on the conditions for exercising Treaty rights as a student has always been publicly available to EU nationals. This can currently be found from page 21 onwards of the guidance on ‘qualified persons’ available on the UKGOV website via the link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/european-economic-area-nationals-qualified-persons" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/european-economic-area-nationals-qualified-persons</a></p><p>The guidance is also attached to this answer.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-16T15:00:09.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681832/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681832/answer","EEA-qualified-persons-v4_0EXT.pdf","EEA-qualified-persons-v4_0EXT.pdf","EEA Qualified Persons","EEA Qualified Persons","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681832/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Overseas Students: EU Nationals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether former higher education students who are EU nationals who apply for permanent residence in the UK are required to have held comprehensive private health insurance during the time during which they were in higher education; and if so, whether students from EU countries are notified of the existence of such a requirement when, or before, they begin their courses of study.","false","Biography information for Lord Beith",,"Lord Beith","HL5145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681833","Department for Education","false","2017-02-06","<p>The £4.4 billion Priority School Building Programme is rebuilding or refurbishing those school buildings in the very worst condition across the country. There are two phases of the programme covering a total of 537 schools.</p><p>Under the first phase of the programme, building work is being undertaken at 260 schools. Of these, 177 schools have already opened in their new and refurbished buildings. This includes 98 secondary schools in 57 local authorities and all are on existing sites.</p><p>The vast majority of schools within the first phase of the programme will be delivered by the end of 2017, two years earlier than originally planned.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-02-06T17:18:26.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681833/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681833/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-31","Priority School Building Programme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government in which education authority areas in England new secondary or high schools have been built under the Priority Schools Building Programme on (1) existing sites, and (2) new sites.","false","Biography information for Lord Beith",,"Lord Beith","HL5146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681834","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-08","<p>There have been no unauthorised incursions by Russian military aircraft into sovereign airspace around the UK, which projects 12 miles off the shore or to a mutually agreed mid-point between adjacent nations, as in the Straits of Dover.</p><p>Russian state registered aircraft, which may include military aircraft, can transit through UK sovereign airspace but must apply for diplomatic clearance in advance on a case by case basis and adhere to an approved flight plan with civil air traffic control authorities.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-08T16:21:05.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681834/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681834/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-31","Russia: Military Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether Russian military aircraft are passing through British airspace; if so, whether they are always required to submit flight plans in advance; and if not so required, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681835","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-14","<p>Average waiting times for telephone calls to be answered by the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency’s (DVLA) contact centre are determined by its automated call monitoring system. The 32 seconds waiting time was the average between April 2016 and January 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2010, the DVLA’s contact centre advisers handle on average 10.6 million calls each year. Over this period, the DVLA has received 72 complaints in the average year about busy lines. A further breakdown to determine specifically those complaints about telephones calls that have not been answered or have been subject to lengthy waiting times is not available.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-02-14T11:57:26.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681835/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681835/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency: Telephone Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 26 January (HL4622) concerning the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency, what survey of incoming telephone calls was undertaken to determine that the average waiting time for calls to be answered is 32 seconds; who undertook the survey; over what period of time it was undertaken; and how many complaints the Agency has received in the average year since 2010 concerning (1) calls not answered, and (2) lengthy waits for calls to be answered.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL5148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681836","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-07","<p>I am withholding the information as its disclosure would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-07T17:10:53.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681836/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681836/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-31","Electronic Warfare","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many cyber attacks on (1) each of the Armed Forces', and (2) the Ministry of Defence, IT networks have been detected over the past year.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL5149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681837","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-13","<p>The Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) and President Trump discussed a range of foreign policy issues during their meeting on 27 January. The UK's position on the location of our embassy has not changed.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-13T14:33:58.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681837/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681837/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-31","Israel: USA","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Prime Minister raised the issue of the location of the US Embassy in Israel with the government of the US during her visit to Washington on 25 to 26 January.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL5150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681838","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-13","<p>The UK's long-standing position is that there can be no sustainable peace in Syria while Asad remains in power. That remains our position. Syria needs a transition to a new, inclusive, non-sectarian government to achieve the credible political settlement that will bring long-term stability. This is set out in the Geneva Communiqué and endorsed by UN Security Council 2254. Any electoral process should be supervised by the United Nations and comprise all 11 million displaced Syrians, including those who have fled to other countries.</p><p>The UK and Russia face a shared threat from terrorism in Syria and we both want to see the defeat of Daesh. We engage with Russia on wider Syria issues. When we believe that Russian actions are prolonging the suffering of the Syrian people, we will make clear our concerns.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-13T14:40:58.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681838/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681838/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-31","Syria: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the evidence given by the Foreign Secretary to the International Relations Committee, when Foreign Office policy towards Syria changed (1) to allow for the possibility that President Bashar al-Assad could stand in a future election in Syria, and (2) to consider the possibility of an arrangement with Russia to combat Daesh and find a way forward over the future of Syria.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL5151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681839","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-13","<p>No - although the United States, like all sovereign nations, reserves the right to conduct border controls.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-13T14:40:31.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681839/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681839/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-31","USA: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether British nationals applying for new ESTAs for travel to the US under the Visa Waiver Program will be subject to additional checks and requirements, including the disclosure of social media information and mobile phone contacts.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL5152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681840","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-13","<p>As the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) said during Prime Minister's Questions on 1 February, we were not given advance notice of the Executive Order before it was signed on 27 January.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-13T14:40:50.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681840/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681840/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-31","USA: Travel Restrictions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they were first made aware of the measures contained in the executive order <i>Protecting The Nation From Foreign Terrorist Entry To The United States</i>, signed by President Trump on 27 January.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL5153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681841","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-14","<p>The United Kingdom complies with EU legislation for nearly all air pollutants, but faces challenges in achieving nitrogen dioxide limits, along with 16 other EU member states. That is why we have committed more than £2 billion since 2011 to reduce transport emissions and the autumn statement provided a further £290 million to support greener transport. Air quality is improving, but the Government recognises that we need to go further and faster and we will be consulting on a new national plan by 24 April. The final plan will be in place by the end of July.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the national air quality plan already in place we are requiring five cities (Birmingham, Derby, Leeds, Nottingham and Southampton) to implement Clean Air Zones.</p><p> </p><p>London faces the greatest challenge because of the size and complexity of the Capital’s transport networks and construction activity from unprecedented growth. The Mayor is responsible for air quality in the capital and has reserve powers under Part IV of the 1995 Environment Act to enable this. Under the Act the Mayor may direct the boroughs in the Greater London area concerning how they should assess and prioritise action in their areas. From September 2020 an Ultra-Low Emission Zone (ULEZ) will be introduced in London. The ULEZ will apply to all cars, motorcycles, vans, minibuses, buses, coaches and HGVs and will cover the same area as the current Congestion Charge Zone.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-02-14T14:15:00.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681841/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681841/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-31","Air Pollution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to ensure that air pollution levels are reduced in the UK, in the light of the alert declared in London recently as a result of toxic air peaks.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL5154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681842","Department of Health","false","2017-02-10","<p>Whilst there is already evidence of the impacts of air pollution on health, and ongoing work to quantify these impacts, the associated costs to the National Health Service and social care budget are less understood. Public Health England (PHE) has commissioned a consortium, led by the UK Health Forum, to carry out a project on the estimation of costs to the NHS and social care due to the health impacts of air pollution as part of PHE’s Health Economics Commissioning Framework. The aim is to enable air pollution to be assessed against other public health threats and to support the strategic priority setting process.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-02-10T09:05:09.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681842/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681842/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-31","Air Pollution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the estimated cost to the NHS of medical problems caused by breaches of air pollution limits.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL5155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681843","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>HM Revenue and Customs’ (HMRC’s) consultation ‘Tobacco Illicit Trade Protocol – licensing of equipment and the supply chain’ sought views on two aspects of the Protocol. These were the mandatory licensing of tobacco manufacturing machinery and the potential licensing of participants in the supply chain of tobacco products for the purposes of tackling the illict trade.</p><p> </p><p>A response document on the licensing of tobacco manufacturing machinery was published on 5 December 2016 and draft legislation was published at the same time.</p><p> </p><p>Licensing of the supply chain is more complex and could affect a large number of UK businesses. Therefore, while HMRC is in a position to proceed to implementation of the licensing of machinery, supply chain licensing requires further consideration. A response document covering this aspect of the consultation will be published later in the year.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-13T15:27:29.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681843/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681843/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Tobacco: Smuggling","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to publish the results of the HMRC consultation <i>Tobacco Illicit Trade Protocol</i> on sanctions to tackle the illicit tobacco market.","true","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL5156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681844","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Environment Agency is planning to issue tender documents for the main component of the works to widen and improve the River Sowy and King Sedgemoor Drain in spring 2017 and expects the scheme to be functional by the end of 2020.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The scheme aims to increase the capacity of the River Sowy and King Sedgemoor Drain system by an estimated 7 cubic metres per second (m<sup>3</sup>/s). This will increase the estimated existing capacity of the system by 41%, from 17 m<sup>3</sup>/s to 24 m<sup>3</sup>/s.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-02-08T14:23:01.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681844/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681844/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-31","Flood Control: Somerset","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 23 January (HL4517), when the scheme to widen and improve the River Sowy and King Sedgemoor Drain will be completed, and what is the estimated increase in volumes of flood water that can be removed as a result of that scheme.","false","Biography information for Lord Patten",,"Lord Patten","HL5157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682228","Attorney General","false","2017-02-07","<p>Civil servants have to have the ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the local Departmental Security teams. Passes can also be issued to contractors or secondees based within Government premises on a case by case basis in regards to specific business needs. Numbers of passes issued directly to non-civil servants for access to departmental buildings will fluctuate over the course of a year.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2017-02-07T16:14:12.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682228/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682228/answer",,,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-01-31","Attorney General: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, which persons not employed by the Law Officers' Departments hold security passes entitling them to enter the Law Officers' Departments premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682229","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-06","Civil servants have to have the ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the local Departmental Security teams. Passes can also be issued to contractors or secondees based within Government premises on a case by case basis in regards to specific business needs. Numbers of passes issued directly to non-civil servants for access to departmental buildings will fluctuate over the course of a year.","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-06T10:49:24.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682229/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682229/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-31","Cabinet Office: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which persons not employed by his Department and its agencies hold security passes entitling them to enter his Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682231","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-03","<p>In 2015, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) invited views from other government departments, enforcement agencies, and representatives of business and public health groups on sanctions and wider action to tackle illicit tobacco. A summary of responses was sent to all respondents to this informal consultation on 15 Jan 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Most respondents recognised the extensive range of criminal and civil sanctions available to HMRC and Border Force or through delivery partners, such as Trading Standards. The consensus was that more could be done to maximise the impact of existing sanctions and to explore additional sanctions with a particular focus on repeat offenders.</p><p> </p><p>The Government announced at Budget 2016 that HMRC would formally consult on a range of proposals for tougher sanctions to tackle this problem. HMRC plans to launch the formal consultation later this year.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-03T11:46:00.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682231/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682231/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Tobacco: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish the results of the HM Revenue and Customs consultation on sanctions for tobacco duty fraud, which closed on 28 August 2015.","false","Biography information for Dr James Davies","Vale of Clwyd","Dr James Davies","62443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682232","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-03","<p>As announced at Budget 2016, the levy will apply to added sugar soft drinks with total sugars above 5 grams per 100 millilitres.</p><p> </p><p>The Government consulted on the detail of the soft drinks industry levy last year. In December 2016, we published our formal response to the consultation, alongside draft Finance Bill legislation, setting out further detail on the scope of the levy and those drinks included.</p><p> </p><p>As for every Finance Bill measure, HM Revenue and Customs published a Tax Impact Information Note which included an updated impact assessment.</p><p> </p><p>The Office for Budget Responsibility has estimated that the levy will raise £520m in the first year, £500 million in the second year, falling to £455m in the third year as more producers reformulate. These estimates are sensitive to the speed of reformulation.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","62471 ; 62472","2017-02-03T12:32:35.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682232/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682232/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what criteria he is using to determine which soft drinks will be subject to the soft drinks industry levy announced in the Budget 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","62470"
