"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682234","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-03","<p>As announced at Budget 2016, the levy will apply to added sugar soft drinks with total sugars above 5 grams per 100 millilitres.</p><p> </p><p>The Government consulted on the detail of the soft drinks industry levy last year. In December 2016, we published our formal response to the consultation, alongside draft Finance Bill legislation, setting out further detail on the scope of the levy and those drinks included.</p><p> </p><p>As for every Finance Bill measure, HM Revenue and Customs published a Tax Impact Information Note which included an updated impact assessment.</p><p> </p><p>The Office for Budget Responsibility has estimated that the levy will raise £520m in the first year, £500 million in the second year, falling to £455m in the third year as more producers reformulate. These estimates are sensitive to the speed of reformulation.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","62470 ; 62471","2017-02-03T12:32:35.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682234/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682234/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Soft Drinks: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the possible negative effect on businesses of the proposed soft drinks industry levy.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","62472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682235","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-03","<p>HM Treasury publishes comprehensive distributional analysis that looks at all of the tax, welfare and public spending changes that affect households. Looking at Tax-Free Childcare in isolation would only present a partial picture of the support the government is providing for families. The last publication from Autumn Statement 2016 can be found online: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/autumn-statement-2016-documents</p><p>The government is updating the impact assessment for Tax-Free Childcare to reflect changes made since the scheme was first announced. It will be published before the scheme launches early this year.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-02-03T10:40:11.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682235/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682235/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what distributional analysis his Department has undertaken of the impact of tax-free childcare.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","62469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682236","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Government believes that tobacco duties achieve a balance between two fiscal goals on tobacco; to raise revenue and to protect public health.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-03T11:46:49.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682236/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682236/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Tobacco: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the point of revenue maximisation on tobacco excise.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","62474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682237","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Government keeps all taxes under review, including alcohol duties, and is always willing to consider any evidence in relation to alcohol taxation policy.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-03T11:48:18.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682237/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682237/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Alcoholic Drinks: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on the UK economy of the freeze in duty on spirits announced in the Budget 2016.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","62488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682238","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-08","<p>Civil servants have to have the ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the Departmental Security teams. Passes can also be issued to contractors or secondees based within government premises on a case by case basis in regards to specific business needs. Numbers of passes issued directly to non-civil servants for access to departmental buildings will fluctuate over the course of a year.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-02-08T15:34:49.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682238/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682238/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Treasury: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which persons not employed by his Department hold security passes entitling them to enter his Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682239","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>We welcome the progress made at recent Libyan economic dialogue meetings in London, Rome and Tunis. The approval by the Libyan Presidency Council (PC) of the budget for 2017 is an important step towards an effective economic policy addressing the most urgent needs of Libya's population.</p><p>Following action under United Nations Security Council Resolution 1973 (2011), Council Regulation (EU) No 204/2011 of 2 March 2011 (consolidated by Council Regulation (EU) No 44/2016) imposed an asset freeze against listed individuals and entities in view of the situation in Libya. The UN Security Council has stipulated that when these are unfrozen, they will be made available to, and for the benefit of the Libyan people. For the duration of time that these assets are frozen, they and any interest they accrue will be governed in accordance with the specific sanctions in place over the individuals or entities to which the assets belong.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-08T14:20:26.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682239/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682239/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-31","Libya: Sanctions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the reported agreement between the Libyan Central Bank and the Government of National Accord and its effect on sanctions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","62595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682240","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-07","<p>Following action at the United Nations, Council Regulation (EU) No 204/2011 of 2 March 2011 imposed an asset freeze against listed individuals and entities in view of the situation in Libya. Council Regulation (EU) No 204/2011 has since been repealed and replaced by Council Regulation (EU) 2016/44 with effect from 20 January 2016. The EU regulation, which has direct effect in the UK, requires that all assets owned or controlled by listed persons are frozen.</p><p> </p><p>The approximate aggregate value of funds frozen in the UK (under EU Regulation 204/2011) was £ 9,467,630,000 at the close of business on 30 September 2015. The figures for the 2016 round of UK frozen funds reporting are in the process of being finalised and as such are not currently available. The frozen funds continue to belong to the individuals and entities listed under the Regulation and are not seized or otherwise held by HM Government. The figure is provided on an aggregate basis so as not to indirectly disclose the value of funds held by particular individuals or entities.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-02-07T10:20:13.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682240/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682240/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Libya: Freezing of Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the total amount of Gaddafi family assets frozen in the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","62598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682241","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-03","<p>The estimated cost of Tax-Free Childcare in each year of this parliament is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>2019-20</p></td><td><p>2020-21</p></td><td><p>2021-22</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cost (£bn)</p></td><td><p>0.0</p></td><td><p>0.6</p></td><td><p>0.8</p></td><td><p>0.9</p></td><td><p>0.9</p></td><td><p>1.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These estimates are published in the Office for Budget Responsibility’s Economic and Fiscal Outlook - November 2016.</p><p><a href="http://budgetresponsibility.org.uk/efo/economic-and-fiscal-outlook-november-2016/" target="_blank">http://budgetresponsibility.org.uk/efo/economic-and-fiscal-outlook-november-2016/</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-02-03T10:41:15.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682241/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682241/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Day Care: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the cost to the public purse of tax-free childcare in each year of this Parliament.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","62615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682242","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-03","<p>Following action at the United Nations, Council Regulation (EU) No 204/2011 of 2 March 2011 imposed an asset freeze against listed individuals and entities in view of the situation in Libya. Council Regulation (EU) No 204/2011 has since been repealed and replaced by Council Regulation (EU) 2016/44 with effect from 20 January 2016. The EU regulation, which has direct effect in the UK, requires that all assets owned or controlled by listed persons are frozen.</p><p> </p><p>The approximate aggregate value of funds frozen in the UK (under EU Regulation 204/2011) was £ 9,467,630,000 at the close of business on 30 September 2015. The figures for the 2016 round of UK frozen funds reporting are in the process of being finalised and as such are not currently available. The frozen funds continue to belong to the individuals and entities listed under the Regulation and are not seized or otherwise held by HM Government. The figure is provided on an aggregate basis so as not to indirectly disclose the value of funds held by particular individuals or entities.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-02-03T12:05:25.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682242/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682242/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Libya: Freezing of Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the value is of the assets of the Gaddafi family that are frozen in the UK.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","62636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682243","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>We do not hold detailed information on receipts and revenue flows from Libya's renewed oil production. What is important is that the resumption of Libya's oil production is sustained to generate the vital revenue needed to enable the Government of National Accord (GNA) to deliver public services and address the needs of the Libyan people: electricity in homes, cash in banks, improving healthcare and infrastructure, for the benefit of all Libyans. Building a safe, secure and prosperous Libya that is able confidently to tackle the challenges in the region is in all our interests.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-07T15:02:59.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682243/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682243/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-31","Libya: Oil","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information his Department holds on whether receipts and revenue flows accruing from Libya's renewed oil production have been deposited or held in UK banking and financial institutions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","62631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682244","Church Commissioners","false","2017-02-06","<p>The security arrangements at Church House in Westminster ensure that employees of the National Church Institutions (NCIs) have full access to those premises whilst others who may need temporary or limited access are able to enter only those parts of the building that they need to access for their work. The system has recently been upgraded to ensure that the NCIs provides a safe environment for staff and visitors.</p><p> </p>","Meriden","Dame Caroline Spelman",,"2017-02-06T16:51:08.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682244/answer","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682244/answer","Meriden","Meriden","Dame Caroline Spelman","Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682244/answer/previousversion/34109","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682244/answer/previousversion/34109","Biography information for Dame Caroline Spelman","9","Church Commissioners","Church Commissioners","2017-01-31","Church Commissioners: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Meriden, representing the Church Commissioners, which persons not employed by the Church Commissioners hold security passes entitling them to enter the Church Commissioners premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682245","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-08","<p>Civil servants have to have the ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the local Departmental Security teams. Passes can also be issued to contractors or secondees based within government premises on a case by case basis in regards to specific business needs. Numbers of passes issued directly to non-civil servants for access to departmental buildings will fluctuate over the course of a year.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-08T16:36:26.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682245/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682245/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Department for Communities and Local Government: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which persons not employed by his Department and its agencies hold security passes entitling them to enter his Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682246","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-07","<p>My Department has not issued any such guidance. It is each local authority's own responsibility to ensure it fulfils its obligations under the Public Sector Equality Duty when making a proposal for a combined authority.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2017-02-07T16:09:47.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682246/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682246/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Combined Authorities: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department has issued to local authorities on engaging with groups with particular protected characteristics covered by the Public Sector Equality Duty when drawing up proposals for a combined authority.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","62583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682247","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-07","<p>My Department has not issued any such guidance. Statute requires that there must be a public consultation - either by the local authorities themselves or the Secretary of State - on any proposal to establish a combined authority, and before proceeding with an order to implement such a proposal, the Secretary of State must be satisfied that no further consultation is necessary.</p>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2017-02-07T16:09:20.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682247/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682247/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Combined Authorities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department has issued to local authorities on their engagement with local communities when drawing up proposals for a combined authority.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","62584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682248","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-03","<p>We have made good progress so far with 189,650 new homes delivered in 2015/16, up 11 per cent on 2014-15. However, there is clearly more to do and our forthcoming White Paper will set out a comprehensive package of reform to deliver the homes this country needs.</p><p>The Department publishes statistics on net additions which are available here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-net-supply-of-housing</p><p><br></p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-02-03T12:45:21.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682248/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682248/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress he has made on building one million new homes by 2020 since the announcement by the Prime Minister on 12 October 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","62610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682249","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-03","<p>Published statistics on the area of designated Green Belt within each local authority area as at 31 March 2016 are available from Annex Table 1 at:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/local-authority-green-belt-statistics-for-england-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/local-authority-green-belt-statistics-for-england-2015-to-2016</a>.</p><p>Published statistics on the area of each local authority as at 31 December 2016 are available from: <a href="http://ons.maps.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=a79de233ad254a6d9f76298e666abb2b" target="_blank">http://ons.maps.arcgis.com/home/item.html?id=a79de233ad254a6d9f76298e666abb2b</a> on the ONS Open Geography Portal. The ‘area to mean high water (coastline)’ measure is used to calculate the National Statistics figure on the proportion of England that is designated Green Belt.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-02-03T12:42:10.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682249/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682249/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682249/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Green Belt: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will estimate the proportion of land designated as greenbelt in each local authority area in the North West.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","62480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682250","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-03","<p>Most non-domestic properties are subject to business rates and set by the independent Valuation Office Agency. The 2016 Budget announced the biggest ever cut in business rates, worth over £6 billion across the next five years. From April 2017 we are permanently doubling the level of Small Business Rate Relief and increasing the thresholds so that 600,000 businesses will pay no business rates at all. We have also given local authorities wide-ranging, discretionary powers to grant business rates discounts. The Government has no plans to offer further relief in respect of community energy projects.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-03T14:45:50.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682250/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682250/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Renewable Energy: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of exempting local community energy projects from business rates.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","62444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682251","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Government has reformed the New Homes Bonus, and the distribution of funding specifically for adult social care was set out in the provisional Local Government Finance Settlement on 15 December 2016.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-08T16:36:48.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682251/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682251/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682251/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answers of 9 January 2017 to Question 58515 and of 18 January 2017 to Question 59298, what plans he has to equalise the payment ratio of new homes bonuses in two-tier local authority areas to help fund social care; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","62435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682252","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-06","<p>Local authorities have wide-ranging powers to grant discretionary relief from business rates to ratepayers. There is nothing preventing authorities from using this power to grant relief to GP surgeries or hospitals. Under the relevant legislation the billing authority must be satisfied that it is reasonable to provide the relief, having regard to the interests of persons liable to pay council tax.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","62420","2017-02-06T17:04:12.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682252/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682252/answer","Nuneaton","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682252/answer/previousversion/34099","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682252/answer/previousversion/34099","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Health Services: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will allow authorities to apply discretionary measures with regard to business rates levied on hospitals and GP surgeries.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","62419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682253","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-06","<p>Local authorities have wide-ranging powers to grant discretionary relief from business rates to ratepayers. There is nothing preventing authorities from using this power to grant relief to GP surgeries or hospitals. Under the relevant legislation the billing authority must be satisfied that it is reasonable to provide the relief, having regard to the interests of persons liable to pay council tax.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","62419","2017-02-06T17:04:12.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682253/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682253/answer","Nuneaton","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682253/answer/previousversion/34100","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682253/answer/previousversion/34100","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Health Services: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, for what reason the proposed new business rates system does not include local authority discretion on business rates levied on hospitals and GP surgeries.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","62420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682254","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-03","<p>Department for Communities and Local Government Ministers have regular discussions with our counterparts at the Department of Health, on a range of matters.</p><p>NHS properties, like almost all other buildings occupied by public bodies, have been subject to non-domestic rates since they were introduced. Operational costs related to property are taken into account at spending reviews in determining the overall level of funding for the NHS.</p><p>A £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme will provide support for the minority of properties which face an increase in rates as a result of the 2017 revaluation, and applies equally to public bodies such as the NHS.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","62422 ; 62423","2017-02-03T13:37:09.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682254/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682254/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Health Services: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the potential change to the costs of NHS operations in (a) Birmingham, Selly Oak constituency, (b) Birmingham and (c) the West Midlands as a result of proposed changes to the business rates system.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","62421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682255","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-03","<p>Department for Communities and Local Government Ministers have regular discussions with our counterparts at the Department of Health, on a range of matters.</p><p>NHS properties, like almost all other buildings occupied by public bodies, have been subject to non-domestic rates since they were introduced. Operational costs related to property are taken into account at spending reviews in determining the overall level of funding for the NHS.</p><p>A £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme will provide support for the minority of properties which face an increase in rates as a result of the 2017 revaluation, and applies equally to public bodies such as the NHS.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","62421 ; 62423","2017-02-03T13:37:09.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682255/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682255/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Health Services: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Health on changes to the business rates system.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","62422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682256","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-03","<p>Department for Communities and Local Government Ministers have regular discussions with our counterparts at the Department of Health, on a range of matters.</p><p>NHS properties, like almost all other buildings occupied by public bodies, have been subject to non-domestic rates since they were introduced. Operational costs related to property are taken into account at spending reviews in determining the overall level of funding for the NHS.</p><p>A £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme will provide support for the minority of properties which face an increase in rates as a result of the 2017 revaluation, and applies equally to public bodies such as the NHS.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","62421 ; 62422","2017-02-03T13:37:09.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682256/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682256/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-31","Health Services: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the proposed increase in business rates for NHS hospitals, GP surgeries and other NHS services on the provision of adult social care.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","62423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682257","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-08","<p>We do not hold data for the number of digitally excluded people resident in the Hemsworth constituency specifically, however the ONS statistical bulletin ‘Internet users in the UK: 2016’ (https://www.ons.gov.uk/businessindustryandtrade/itandinternetindustry/bulletins/internetusers/2016) indicates an estimated 10.9% of adults in the surrounding area of Calderdale, Kirklees and Wakefield had never used the internet or had last used the internet more than three months previously. This compares to an estimated 12% of adults in the UK who had never used the internet or had last used the internet more than three months previously.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises the effect digital exclusion has on individuals and their ability to confidently use the internet, including their capacity to bank online safely and effectively. The Government is actively tackling the barriers to inclusion, working with cross-sector partners, including in the banking sector, to promote the financial, social, health and wellbeing benefits of being online. Some banks are directly addressing digital exclusion. For example, Lloyds and Barclays have trained their staff to support digitally excluded people.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-08T14:34:57.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682257/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682257/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-31","Digital Technology: Hemsworth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate she has made of the number of digitally excluded people resident in Hemsworth constituency; and what assessment she has made of the effects of digital exclusion on their capacity to bank online safely and effectively.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682258","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-06","<p>At grassroots level, government is investing funding of £1.7 m between 2017 and 2021 in British Fencing. The recently published Active Lives survey shows that 25,000 people in England regularly take part in fencing. On Friday 3 February Sport England announced that it will be investing a further £500,000 in British Fencing to support talented fencers with a potential further £500,000 to be invested in the future.</p><p> </p><p>At elite level, Wheelchair Fencing will receive £668,000 during the 2017-21 Tokyo Paralympic Cycle, increased from £194,886 during the 2013-17 Rio cycle.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-02-06T13:38:33.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682258/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682258/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-31","Fencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to promote interest in fencing.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","62635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682259","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-07","<p>Civil servants have to have the ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the local Departmental Security teams. Passes can also be issued to contractors or secondees based within Government premises on a case by case basis in regards to specific business needs. Numbers of passes issued directly to non-civil servants for access to departmental buildings will fluctuate over the course of a year.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-07T11:38:40.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682259/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682259/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-31","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, which persons not employed by her Department and its agencies hold security passes entitling them to enter her Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682260","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-08","<p>The money will be returned to local authorities through their existing broadband contracts, based on the levels of savings achieved and levels of take-up, and will be available for them to reinvest in further superfast rollout.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-08T14:31:42.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682260/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682260/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-31","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to her Department's news story of 22 December 2016, how the £440 million made available for superfast rural broadband will be (a) allocated between and (b) managed by local authorities.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","62521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682261","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-08","<p>There are approximately 45,750 premises in the constituency of Coventry South. Over 89% of the constituency can currently get superfast broadband, with just over 4900 premises without superfast availability at the moment.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-02-08T14:30:36.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682261/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682261/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-31","Broadband: Coventry South","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate her Department has made of how many premises in Coventry South constituency do not have access to superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","62498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682262","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Iraq Historic Allegations Team (IHAT) operates within an agreed lifetime budget of £57.2 million.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-02-06T16:58:47.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682262/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682262/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682262/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-31","Iraq Historic Allegations Team","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 12 December 2016 to Question 56187, what the budget is for the Iraq Historic Allegations Team in (a) 2017-18 and (b) 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Sir Henry Bellingham","North West Norfolk","Sir Henry Bellingham","62501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682263","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-06","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 31 January to the hon. Member for Rutherglen and Hamilton West (Ms Ferrier) to Question 61464. HMS Vengeance successfully concluded her Demonstration and Shakedown Operation and returned to the operational cycle.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","62562 ; 62655","2017-02-06T16:32:48.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682263/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682263/answer","20170131_61464_WQnA_extract_on_Trident_Missile_Testing.docx","20170131_61464_WQnA_extract_on_Trident_Missile_Testing.docx","61464 - WQnA extract on Trident Missile Testing","61464 - WQnA extract on Trident Missile Testing","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682263/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-31","Trident Missiles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what criteria underpinned the decision not to make public the fact that the 2016 Demonstration and Shakedown Operation exercise had not been completed as planned and that the Trident D5 II missile launched by HMS Vanguard had not completed its test as planned.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","62565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682264","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-06","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 26 January 2017 to the hon. Member for South Down (Ms Ritchie) to Question 61284. HMS Vengeance successfully concluded her Demonstration and Shakedown Operation and returned to the operational cycle.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","62558 ; 62559 ; 62560","2017-02-06T16:58:11.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682264/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682264/answer","20170126_61284_WQnA_extract_on_Trident_Missiles_Testing.docx","20170126_61284_WQnA_extract_on_Trident_Missiles_Testing.docx","WQnA extract on Trident Missiles Testing","WQnA extract on Trident Missiles Testing","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682264/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-31","Trident Missiles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how soon after he took office was the Prime Minister informed by his Department that the Trident D5 II missile launched as part of the 2016 Demonstration and Shakedown Operation exercise had not completed its test as planned.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","62561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682265","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-06","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 23 January to the hon. Member for North Durham (Kevan Jones) (Vol 620, Col 23). Details of the Trident weapon system and submarine operations must remain secret. The Government is in no doubt about the capability and effectiveness of the Trident missile system. HMS Vengeance successfully concluded her Demonstration and Shakedown Operation and returned to the operational cycle.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","62522 ; 62523 ; 62556 ; 62557 ; 62564","2017-02-06T16:57:10.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682265/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682265/answer","20170123_UQ_on_Trident_Test_Firing.docx","20170123_UQ_on_Trident_Test_Firing.docx","Hansard extract on Trident Test Firing","Hansard extract on Trident Test Firing","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682265/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-31","Trident Missiles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department holds on the (a) nature and (b) incidence of faults in the navigation controls on the Trident D5 II missiles.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","62563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682266","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-06","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 23 January to the hon. Member for North Durham (Kevan Jones) (Vol 620, Col 23). Details of the Trident weapon system and submarine operations must remain secret. The Government is in no doubt about the capability and effectiveness of the Trident missile system. HMS Vengeance successfully concluded her Demonstration and Shakedown Operation and returned to the operational cycle.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","62522 ; 62523 ; 62556 ; 62557 ; 62563","2017-02-06T16:57:10.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682266/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682266/answer","20170123_UQ_on_Trident_Test_Firing.docx","20170123_UQ_on_Trident_Test_Firing.docx","Hansard extract on Trident Test Firing","Hansard extract on Trident Test Firing","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682266/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-31","Trident Missiles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Inertial Guidance System on board the Trident D5 II missile was tested during the 2016 Demonstration and Shakedown exercise.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","62564"
