"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682374","Home Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>Individual forces in Liverpool, Merseyside and England record incidents involving off-road motorcycles. This Information is not held centrally.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-02-07T16:20:16.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682374/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682374/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Motorcycles: Road Traffic Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many incidents involving off-road motorcycles have been recorded by police forces in (a) Liverpool, (b) Merseyside and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","62403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682375","Home Office","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Security Industry Authority (SIA) is an Executive Non-Departmental Body (NDPB) of the Home Office. The SIA is operationally independent.</p><p>The SIA is accountable for its own complaints procedures and ensuring that these operate effectively. As with other NDPBs, the Home Secretary appoints the Chair and non-executive members of the SIA Board, and the Department ensures the SIA is subject to regular and ongoing oversight in relation to its performance.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-02-03T14:42:34.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682375/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682375/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Security Industry Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what role her Department and its agencies play in the oversight of the operation by the Security Industry Authority of its complaints procedures; what regulatory role she plays in connection with that authority; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","62413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682376","Home Office","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Security Industry Authority (SIA) is not under a legal duty to provide complainants with details of any investigations, outcomes or actions relating to the complaints they have made, nor to disclose details of actions taken as a result of an investigation into alleged criminality by licence holders.</p><p> </p><p>Where prosecutions are completed, the outcomes, which are a matter of public record, are published on the SIA website: <a href="http://www.sia.homeoffice.gov.uk/Pages/enforcement-prosecutions.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.sia.homeoffice.gov.uk/Pages/enforcement-prosecutions.aspx</a></p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","62408","2017-02-03T10:27:03.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682376/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682376/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Security Industry Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what duty the Security Industry Authority has to provide complainants with the details of any investigations, outcomes or actions relating to the complaints they have made.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","62407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682377","Home Office","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Security Industry Authority (SIA) is not under a legal duty to provide complainants with details of any investigations, outcomes or actions relating to the complaints they have made, nor to disclose details of actions taken as a result of an investigation into alleged criminality by licence holders.</p><p> </p><p>Where prosecutions are completed, the outcomes, which are a matter of public record, are published on the SIA website: <a href="http://www.sia.homeoffice.gov.uk/Pages/enforcement-prosecutions.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.sia.homeoffice.gov.uk/Pages/enforcement-prosecutions.aspx</a></p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","62407","2017-02-03T10:27:03.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682377/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682377/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Security Industry Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Security Industry Authority is required to disclose details of actions taken as a result of an investigation into alleged criminality by licence holders.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","62408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682378","Home Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>All asylum claims lodged in the UK are carefully considered on their individual merits against a background of relevant case law and up to date country information. We ensure that claimants are given every opportunity to disclose information relevant to their claim before a decision is taken, even where that information may be sensitive or difficult to disclose.</p><p> </p><p>We are working to improve the quality of decision-making to ensure that we properly consider all the evidence provided and get decisions right the first time. UK Visas and Immigration has an internal audit process, consisting of reviews by senior case workers and independent auditors, which assesses whether Home Office policy has been followed.</p><p> </p><p>An allowed appeal is not in itself an indication that our decision was incorrect at the time it was made though we aim to reduce the allowed appeal rate by analysing the reasons why appeals are allowed and using this to further improve guidance and training.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-06T14:03:21.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682378/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682378/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to (a) ensure that the initial discussions on asylum applications are correct and (b) reduce the number of asylum decisions overturned at appeal.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","62574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682379","Home Office","false","2017-02-03","<p>Asylum Operations recently received funding from the Asylum Migration and Integration Fund to review and redevelop its training prospectus.</p><p> </p><p>The current training for asylum decision making staff involves a dedicated five week course (or ‘Foundation Training Programme’) which covers Asylum legislation, the Refugee Convention, Human Rights law, UK Immigration Rules and legislation, as well as training on conducting asylum interviews and decisions.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-03T14:55:53.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682379/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682379/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the training module developed for asylum caseworkers has been fully implemented.","false","Biography information for Dr Alasdair McDonnell","Belfast South","Dr Alasdair McDonnell","62611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682380","Home Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The common groups of persons who are not employed by the Department but have the appropriate level of clearance to hold security passes entitling them to enter Departmental premises are: holders of judicial office, non-executive directors, contractors, agency staff, and holders of the common civil service pass.</p><p> </p><p>Temporary staff and visitors to the Department’s buildings are issued with an escorted or unescorted day pass subject to the level of their security clearance.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-06T16:01:32.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682380/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682380/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Home Office: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which persons not employed by her Department and its agencies hold security passes entitling them to enter her Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682381","Home Office","false","2017-02-03","<p>I am sorry but the Home Office does not record this information centrally and it could only be provided at disproportionate cost by examination of individual records.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-03T10:33:35.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682381/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682381/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum seekers in (a) the UK and (b) Scotland were housed in initial accommodation for longer than the 17 day target period, in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","62575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682382","Home Office","false","2017-02-03","<p>I am sorry but the data requested could only be provided at disproportionate cost by examination of individual records.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-03T10:28:28.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682382/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682382/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Home Office torture evidence assessments were judicially appealed by asylum seekers in 2016; and how many such appeals overturned a Home Office assessment on whether an asylum seeker had experienced torture.","false","Biography information for Dr Alasdair McDonnell","Belfast South","Dr Alasdair McDonnell","62612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682383","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-08","<p>The undertaking made in 1977 continues to be Government policy, but it was regrettably breached on occasions during operations in Iraq in circumstances described fully in the Report of the Baha Mousa Inquiry (HC1452) published on 8 September 2011. Remedial action to prevent any recurrence was taken in accordance with the recommendations of the Inquiry.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-02-08T16:15:47.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682383/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682383/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-31","Internment: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the undertaking given by the then Attorney-General on 8 February 1977, that the five techniques of questioning used in Northern Ireland in 1971, have not in any circumstances been reintroduced since then as an aid to interrogation; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","62619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682384","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-02-08T10:20:01.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682384/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682384/answer","PQ62514 Holding Response.pdf","PQ62514 Holding Response.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Data of Incidence","UKSA Letter to Member - Data of Incidence","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682384/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-31","Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 24 January 2017 to Question 60953, if he will place in the Library summary data on the incidence and prevalence of (a) cyber-enabled crime, (b) plastic payment card fraud and (c) other similar technology crimes in each year between 1999 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","62514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682385","Home Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>Data on the numbers of asylum seekers specifically in Cambridge cannot be provided without incurring disproportionate cost because checks of individual records would be required.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-08T17:09:34.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682385/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682385/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Asylum: Cambridge","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for how many (a) Case Assurance and Audit Unit and (b) legacy cases her Department has records of people who reside in Cambridge.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","62499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682386","House of Commons Commission","false","2017-02-14","<p>Persons not employed by the House of Commons Commission who hold security passes entitling them to enter the House of Commons estate are:</p><ul><li>Members of the House of Commons and their spouses/partners</li><li>Members of the House of Lords and their spouses/partners</li><li>Staff of Members of both Houses, political party staff sponsored by Members and staff of party research units</li><li>Staff of the House of Lords</li><li>Contractors</li><li>Members of the Metropolitan Police contracted by Parliament</li><li>Government officials</li><li>Specialist staff of parliamentary bodies</li><li>Specialist Advisers</li><li>Roll A Agents &amp; specified legal advisers used by the House</li><li>Media</li><li>Union representatives for House staff</li><li>Former Members of both Houses</li><li>Retired senior parliamentary officials</li><li>Residents of the Parliamentary Estate</li></ul>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2017-02-14T14:31:27.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682386/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682386/answer",,,,,,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2017-01-31","House of Commons Commission: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, which persons not employed by the House of Commons Commission hold security passes entitling them to enter the House of Commons Commission's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682387","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-07","<p>Spending 0.7% of Gross National Income on Official Development Assistance (ODA) is a UK commitment which is firmly in the national interest. In order to respond to the new global challenges, the UK Aid Strategy sets out the need to deploy the wider skills and expertise of all parts of government.</p><p>Accounting officers of departments or public bodies whose money is being spent on aid need to ensure they fulfil their obligations under HM Treasury’s ‘Managing Public Money’, including ensuring value for money of the use of public funds.</p><p>The International Development Act places an obligation on the Secretary of State to ensure the independent evaluation of UK ODA.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-07T15:39:53.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682387/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682387/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-31","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 18 January 2017 to Question 59290, for what reasons other Departments have Official Development Assistance (ODA) budgets; and if she will review the effectiveness of the ODA budgets of other Departments to ensure value for money for the public purse.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682388","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-07","<p><em> O</em>DA spend by other departments is available from the National Statistics publication, Statistics on International Development:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/572073/table-a-3a.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/572073/table-a-3a.ods</a></p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-07T15:40:32.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682388/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682388/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-31","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 18 January 2017 to Question 59290, what the value of other Departments' Official Development Assistance budgets was for each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","62593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682389","Department for International Development","true","2017-02-07","<p>Civil servants have to have the ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. Passes may also be issued to <ins class="ministerial">contractors or secondees</ins> where there is an identified business need for them to enter Department for International Development premises, subject to the usual security checks. For security reasons it would not be appropriate to provide details of individuals who hold such passes.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-07T15:46:14.823Z","2017-02-07T17:17:20.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682389/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682389/answer","Penrith and The Border","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682389/answer/previousversion/34471","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682389/answer/previousversion/34471","Biography information for Rory Stewart","20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-31","Department for International Development: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which persons not employed by her Department hold security passes entitling them to enter her Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682390","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-08","<p>The UK has a strong history of protecting human rights and promoting our values globally. We will in due course consider all options in the design of future bilateral trade and investment agreements. We will of course continue to honour our international human rights obligations.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-08T15:28:43.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682390/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682390/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-31","Overseas Trade: European Convention on Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the role the European Convention of Human Rights in future trade deals the UK makes with other countries.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","62404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682391","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-07","<p>Civil servants have to have the ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the local Departmental Security teams. Passes can also be issued to contractors or secondees based within Government premises on a case by case basis in regards to specific business needs. Numbers of passes issued directly to non-civil servants for access to departmental buildings will fluctuate over the course of a year.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-07T16:16:43.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682391/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682391/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-31","Ministry of Justice: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which persons not employed by her Department and its agencies hold security passes entitling them to enter her Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682392","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-08","<p>On 2 February the Government published a White Paper setting out its objectives and plans for the new partnership we want to build with the EU. Following their publication, my Department will place in the Library any public consultations or White Papers it publishes relevant to the United Kingdom’s preparation for a successful exit from the European Union.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-08T17:50:20.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682392/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682392/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-31","Ministry of Justice: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will place in the Library a list of public consultations, White Papers and other documents her Department plans to publish to assist the UK in making effective the Government's plans for the UK to leave the EU within the two year timetable from the triggering of Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty.","false","Biography information for Michael Gove","Surrey Heath","Michael Gove","62507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682394","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>I am not aware of any specific information held by my Department in relation to this matter.</p><p> </p><p>It is my understanding, however, that the Republic of Ireland gave further effect to provisions of the Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms in domestic legislation through the European Convention of Human Rights Act 2003, and that since 1998 a number of pieces of legislation have been introduced in the Republic of Ireland including the Employment Equality Acts 1998 and 2004.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-02-07T12:02:42.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682394/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682394/answer",,,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-31","Belfast Agreement: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what information his Department holds on whether the Republic of Ireland has introduced equal status legislation since 10 April 1998 as provided by paragraph 9 of the chapter on rights, safeguarding and equality of opportunity in the Belfast Agreement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","62551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682395","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>Following their publication, my Department will place in the Library any public consultations or White Papers it publishes relevant to the United Kingdom’s preparation for a successful exit from the European Union.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-02-08T11:25:14.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682395/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682395/answer",,,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-31","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, if he will place in the Library a list of public consultations, White Paper and other documents his Department plans to publish to assist the UK in making effective the Government's plans for the UK to leave the EU within the two year timetable from the triggering of Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty.","false","Biography information for Michael Gove","Surrey Heath","Michael Gove","62509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682396","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Northern Ireland Office issues passes to persons not employed by the Department who have the relevant security clearance and are contracted to provide corporate or security services which require them to enter the premises. Additionally, the department supplies such passes to security cleared contractors to maintain on-site equipment.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-02-07T12:04:25.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682396/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682396/answer",,,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-31","Northern Ireland Office: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, which persons not employed by his Department hold security passes entitling them to enter his Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682397","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-03","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the right hon. Member for Islington North (Mr Corbyn) on 1 February 2017, Official Report, column 1015.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","62415","2017-02-03T14:12:10.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682397/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682397/answer",,,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-31","USA: Travel Restrictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether her Government had advance knowledge of the intention of the US Administration to issue an executive order to restrict immigration on 27 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","62414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682398","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-03","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the right hon. Member for Islington North (Mr Corbyn) on 1 February 2017, Official Report, column 1015.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","62414","2017-02-03T14:12:10.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682398/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682398/answer",,,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-31","USA: Travel Restrictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether, during her recent visit to the US, (a) the issue of the US Administration's intention to issue an executive order to restrict immigration and (b) any potential impact of that order on British citizens were discussed.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","62415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682399","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-03","<p>Officials and advisers have meetings with a wide range of individuals and organisations on a wide range of subjects.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-02-03T14:10:42.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682399/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682399/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682399/answer",,,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-31","Myron Ebell","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, who was present at the meeting with Myron Ebell at Number 10 Downing Street on 31 January 2017; what was discussed at that meeting; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","62486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682400","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-07","<p>Following the practice followed by past administrations, the Government does not comment on security matters.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-02-07T16:51:58.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682400/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682400/answer",,,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-31","Prime Minister: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, which persons not employed by 10 Downing Street hold security passes entitling them to enter 10 Downing Street premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682401","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-08","<p>During the passage of the Pensions Bill 2011, the Government has made a concession worth £1.1 billion to limit the impact of State Pension age increases for those women most affected by them. As a consequence, no women will experience increases of more than 18 months compared to the previous timetable.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-02-08T14:42:58.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682401/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682401/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682401/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Oral Answer of 25 January 2017, column 295, what extra money the Government has put into reducing the changes in women's pensions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","62618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682402","Scotland Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>Civil servants have to have the ability to work flexibly across Government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the local Departmental Security teams. Passes can also be issued to contractors or secondees based within Government premises on a case by case basis in regards to specific business needs. Numbers of passes issued directly to non-civil servants for access to departmental buildings will fluctuate over the course of a year.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-02-06T15:22:49.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682402/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682402/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-01-31","Scotland Office: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, which persons not employed by his Department hold security passes entitling them to enter his Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682403","Scotland Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Department for Exiting the EU is leading the UK government’s efforts on exiting the EU, and as the Prime Minister has said, we do not approach these negotiations expecting failure, but anticipating success.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Exiting the EU published a White Paper on ‘The United Kingdom’s exit from and new partnership with the European Union’ on Thursday 2 February.</p><p> </p><p>I and my officials will continue to work closely with other parts of the UK Government and the Scottish Government, and we will continue to engage stakeholders in Scotland.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-02-06T15:24:16.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682403/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682403/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-01-31","Scotland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, if he will place in the Library a list of public consultations, White Paper and other documents his Department plans to publish to assist the UK in making effective the Government's plans for the UK to leave the EU within the two year timetable from the triggering of Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty.","false","Biography information for Michael Gove","Surrey Heath","Michael Gove","62505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682404","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>On 2 February the Government published a White Paper setting out its objectives and plans for the new partnership we want to build with the EU. The Department currently has no plans for further publications. Any future publications would be deposited in the library of the House in the usual way.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-07T13:31:08.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682404/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682404/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Department for Transport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will place in the Library a list of public consultations, White Paper and other documents his Department plans to publish to assist the UK in making effective the Government's plans for the UK to leave the EU within the two year timetable from the triggering of Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty.","false","Biography information for Michael Gove","Surrey Heath","Michael Gove","62506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682405","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Government is committed to meeting its emissions reduction targets under the Climate Change Act. On the 2 February, alongside laying the Airport National Policy Statement, the Secretary of State for Transport set out his intention to develop a new Aviation Strategy in which we will look to address the issue of the sector’s climate change impacts. We remain open and willing to consider all feasible measures to ensure that the aviation sector contributes fairly to UK emissions reductions. The first stage in developing the Strategy will be a Call for Evidence in the spring.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-07T13:38:48.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682405/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682405/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Aviation: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the upcoming aviation strategy will outline how the UK will limit aviation emissions to at least below 2005 levels by 2050.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","62503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682406","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>While the global aviation fleet is expected to double over the next 20 years, action taken by the industry, governments and the International Civil Aviation Organisation (ICAO) to effect carbon reduction means that the total carbon emissions from the sector will not rise in line with growth in demand. This will be achieved through a combination of factors, including the development and adoption of new technologies, operational efficiencies, greater use of sustainable aviation fuels, and offsetting through schemes such as that agreed at last year’s ICAO Assembly.</p><p> </p><p>Specifically, the International Air Transport Association (IATA) has committed, on behalf of the global aviation sector, to continuously improve the CO<sub>2</sub> efficiency of civil aircraft by an average of 1.5 per cent per annum from 2009 until 2020, to achieve carbon neutral growth from 2020, and to reduce its carbon emissions by 50 per cent by 2050 compared to 2005 levels.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-07T13:43:03.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682406/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682406/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Aviation: Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to his speech to Airlines UK on 25 January 2017, on what grounds he asserts that the doubling of the world's aircraft fleet over the next 20 years and the introduction of cleaner and more efficient aircraft will deliver a fall in global carbon emissions.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","62511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682407","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-08","<p>There are different categories of persons who for business needs require access to the Department’s premises. Outside of permanent civil servants this includes contractors or secondees and the number of passes issued will fluctuate across any given time period. Departmental and Agency Security teams manage the end to end processes of issuing, return and destruction of security passes.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-08T15:12:23.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682407/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682407/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Department for Transport: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which persons not employed by his Department hold security passes entitling them to enter his Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682408","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Department is determined to improve the provision of roadside toilets and other facilities for HGV drivers, through working with stakeholders in a number of areas. It is developing with representative groups what will be official standards for facilities at Motorway Service Areas. This is part of wider work also involving improved planning, ensuring high standards more generally including at truck stops and making sure that delivery drivers have access to toilets at customer sites. This work is being informed by a systematic parking survey for completion in the Spring which will help in understanding where more facilities are most needed.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-07T13:26:58.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682408/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682408/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers: Facilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his Department's policy is on the provision of roadside toilets and other facilities for HGV drivers.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","62578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682409","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-06","<p>The <em>UK Airspace Policy: A framework for balanced decisions on the design and use of airspace consultation</em> was published on 2 February 2017.</p><p> </p><p>A copy of this document has been placed in the Library.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-06T11:26:37.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682409/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682409/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether a publication date has been set for his Department's review of airspace modernisation and noise policies in the UK.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","62577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682410","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Department for Transport has been actively participating in negotiations on the revision of the European Aviation Safety Agency’s (EASA) Basic Regulation, which will include EU-wide safety rules for all unmanned aircraft.</p><p> </p><p>EASA is currently in the process of drafting its proposed harmonised European rules for the ‘Open’ and ‘Specific’ categories of drones. This proposal is planned to go out to consultation at the end of March 2017. The Civil Aviation Authority participates in the EASA Expert Group of subject matter experts, and is assisting with the development of the proposal.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s consultation on the safe use of drones in the UK closes on 15 March 2017. There are several proposals contained within which may require updated regulation. We will continue to feed relevant UK experience into the EASA process; in particular, to ensure continued support for the development of a proportionate regulatory framework.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-03T13:10:38.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682410/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682410/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Aviation: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress his Department is making through the European Aviation Safety Agency to update common drone regulations; and in what ways he intends his Department's consultation on the safe use of drones in the UK to support that process.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","62613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682411","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-03","<p>My Department sets out how we will enforce measures in rail franchise agreements in its ‘enforcement policy: rail franchise agreements and closures’, published on the website.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/enforcement-policy-rail-franchise-agreements-and-closures" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/enforcement-policy-rail-franchise-agreements-and-closures</a></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-03T10:22:35.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682411/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682411/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what remedies are available to him, in addition to removing the franchise from Govia Thameslink Railway, if that company is in default of its franchise agreement.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","62409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682412","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-03","<p>The scale of the industrial action on Southern has caused significant disruption to passengers, which is reflected in the force majeure claim by Govia Thameslink Railway. The Department analyses claims and must be satisfied that force majeure is appropriate. This is a complex claim to analyse and the process is ongoing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Whether GTR meets performance benchmarks will be affected by the outcome of the force majeure claim. If the force majeure claim is not agreed, or agreed in part only, the Secretary of State will consider appropriate remedial action.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-03T10:24:06.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682412/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682412/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether Govia Thameslink Railway will be in default of its franchise agreement if its applications for force majeure are not agreed by his Department.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","62410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682413","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Rail Vehicle Accessibility (Non-Interoperable Rail System) Regulations 2010 standards apply to non-mainline operations (such as trams, light rail and metro systems). Accessibility standards for trains operated on the mainline are either the Rail Vehicle Accessibility Regulations 1998 or the Persons of Reduced Mobility Technical Specification for Interoperability (PRM-TSI) (under the Railways (Interoperability) Regulations 2011).</p><p> </p><p>Thameslink is in the process of commissioning and operating 1140 brand new Class 700 vehicles, which are PRM-TSI compliant. The following units are built to the standards mandated in the Rail Vehicle Accessibility Regulations 1998:</p><p> </p><p>Class 171 (6 x4 car units plus 10 x 2 car units), Class 377/1 (64 x 4 car units), Class 377/2 (15 x 4 car units), Class 377/3 (28 x 3 car units), 377/4 (75 x 4 car units), class 377/5 (23 x 4 car units).</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-03T12:59:57.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682413/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682413/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern Franchise: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which vehicles operated on the Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern Franchise are (a) compliant and (b) not compliant with the Rail Vehicle Accessibility (Non-Interoperable Rail System) Regulations 2010.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","62411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682414","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-03","<p>No exemptions have been requested for these vehicles in the period 2014 to date.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-03T10:25:53.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682414/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682414/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern Franchise: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what exemptions have been given for vehicles operated on the Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern Franchise since that franchise began; and when those exemptions were granted.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","62412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682415","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-03","<p>We have begun the process of developing a new strategy for UK aviation. This will be an ambitious programme of work, and we will be consulting widely throughout 2017, leading to publication of an Aviation Strategy White Paper at the end of 2018.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-03T11:37:14.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682415/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682415/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682415/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects the Aviation Strategy to be published.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","62418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682416","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-08","<p>No such assessment has been made. The Chancellor of the Exchequer considers all aspects of taxation as part of the Budget process.</p><p> </p><p>Cars first registered from 1 April 2017 onwards will pay a first year rate that varies by carbon emissions, followed by a flat standard rate of £140, except zero emission cars, which continue to pay nothing. Cars worth over £40,000 will pay a £310 supplement for the first five years of the standard rate, irrespective of whether they are conventionally fuelled, hybrid or electric cars.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-08T15:52:05.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682416/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682416/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682416/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of changes to vehicle excise duty from April 2017 on the rate of early scrappage of private cars.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","62426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682417","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>The table below details the number of agency staff working for the department in each of the last 12 months. This response covers the central department and its four executive agencies.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January</p></td><td><p>120</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February</p></td><td><p>117</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March</p></td><td><p>116</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April</p></td><td><p>94</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May</p></td><td><p>104</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June</p></td><td><p>102</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July</p></td><td><p>99</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August</p></td><td><p>99</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September</p></td><td><p>99</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October</p></td><td><p>101</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November</p></td><td><p>102</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December</p></td><td><p>106</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-07T13:24:08.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682417/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682417/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682417/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Department for Transport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many agency staff his Department has employed in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","62492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682418","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Department does not hold any information about whether drivers of lorries or any other vehicles were using or had access to satellite navigation systems when they were involved in an incident or accident.</p><p> </p><p>Satellite navigation systems are a useful driving aid, but they are not a replacement for lorry drivers observing road signs, the wider road environment and using their training effectively.</p><p>The Department has invested £3 million in working with Ordnance Survey on a new digital map of the road network. This will make it easier for drivers to navigate Britain's roads. By bringing more information on restrictions together it will also help businesses by reducing time and money wasted by lorry drivers taking roads unsuitable for their vehicles.</p><p> </p><p>The first full commercial release of the map was in October 2016 and it is updated each month.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-08T14:04:08.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682418/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682418/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682418/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Large Goods Vehicles: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of traffic incidents or accidents caused by lorries relying on satellite navigation devices designated for cars in the last 12 months; and if he will look at ways of discouraging HGV drivers from using such devices.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","62526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682419","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>Following the accident in April 2016, the UK Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) has been in regular contact with all interested parties including Airbus helicopters, the European Aviation Safety Agency, Norwegian authorities, helicopter operators, the offshore industry and workforce representatives. Department for Transport officials have also had discussions with Airbus Helicopters.</p><p> </p><p>The Norwegian accident investigation team has published interim reports on its progress investigating the accident. Its work continues and a final report has not yet been published.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Air Accident Investigation Branch is assisting the Accident Investigation Board of Norway (AIBN) under European and International protocols, and has been involved in their discussions with the manufacturer. The AIBN are conducting the investigation and any information on the investigation and progress will be released and published by them.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-07T13:34:38.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682419/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682419/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682419/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Helicopters: Norway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department has had with Airbus Helicopters on (a) Airbus' internal investigations into the accident at Turøy in April 2016 and (b) progress made in identifying with the Accident Investigation Board for Norway the causes of that accident.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","62445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682420","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-03","<p>No internationally registered vessels were detained by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency for infringement of the provisions of Annex VI of the International Convention for the Prevention of Pollution from Ships in either 2015 or 2016.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-03T11:40:22.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682420/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682420/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682420/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Shipping: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which internationally registered vessels were detained by the Maritime and Coastguard Agency for infringement of the provisions of Annex VI of the International Convention for the Prevention of Pollution from Ships in (a) 2015 and (b) 2016.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","62467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682421","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Department for Transport (DfT) works closely with the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) and industry to adapt and strengthen regulations and implement mitigations as drone use and the related technology evolves.</p><p> </p><p>The Air Navigation Order 2016 sets out several rules which drone users must abide by. In particular, users must not fly drones with cameras within 50m of any vehicle, structure or person which is not under the control of the person in charge of the aircraft. They must also not fly drones over or within 150m of any congested area or large crowds of people.</p><p> </p><p>Permitted distances will vary dependent on factors such as the structure or area that the drone is in proximity to and may also vary depending on the category of drone (e.g. for drones of a particular weight, or those with or without cameras). As there is no internationally agreed definition of “safe distance” it is difficult to make comparisons with other countries. However, we are collaborating internationally to share learning and best practice.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is currently consulting on the future safe use of drones in the UK, and the DfT and CAA will consider reviewing these regulatory requirements for drone activity on the basis of the consultation responses. The consultation can be found on gov.uk and closes on 15 March 2017.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-03T13:11:52.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682421/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682421/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682421/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-31","Aviation: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with (a) the Civil Aviation Authority and (b) external groups, regarding the Civil Aviation Authority's definition of a safe distance used for regulating drone activity; and how that definition compares with those used by other countries.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","62466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682422","Wales Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>On 2 February, the Government published a White Paper entitled ‘The United Kingdom’s exit from and new partnership with the European Union’. The Wales Office will continue to support the Department for Exiting the European Union as we work towards the 12 negotiating objectives set out in this paper. I have no plans to publish any documents related to this work.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-02-06T10:56:28.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682422/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682422/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682422/answer",,,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-01-31","Wales Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, if he will place in the Library a list of public consultations, White Paper and other documents his Department plans to publish to assist the UK in making effective the Government's plans for the UK to leave the EU within the two year timetable from the triggering of Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty.","false","Biography information for Michael Gove","Surrey Heath","Michael Gove","62508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682423","Home Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Home Office has engaged closely with other Government departments through the Violence Against Women and Girls (VAWG) Inter-Ministerial Group to oversee delivery of the VAWG strategy including the commitment of increased funding of £80m for VAWG services.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office has also engaged closely with commissioners and voluntary sector partners on support for independent domestic violence advisers, and our move to support better local collaboration and early intervention through the VAWG Service Transformation Fund.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-06T15:58:24.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682423/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682423/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682423/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-31","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with the Home Office on the Government's proposal to continue direct grant funding to support independent domestic violence advisers and multi-agency risk assessment conference coordinators after March 2017.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","62446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682424","Department for Education","false","2017-02-07","<p>Volunteers are not covered by the Equality Act 2010 (the Act) because they do not meet the definition of an employee under the Act, a position confirmed by the Supreme Court in the case of <em>X v Mid Sussex Citizens Advice Bureau [2012]. </em>We have no plans to change this.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-07T11:44:37.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682424/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682424/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682424/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-31","Voluntary Work: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will amend the Equality Act 2010, or bring forward new legislation, to protect volunteers from encountering discrimination in the workplace.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","62447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682425","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-08","<p>We will be undertaking an equality analysis as part of the detailed planning for service reconfiguration. This will include feedback from public consultation in those locations where this applies.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-08T14:36:26.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682425/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682425/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682425/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Jobcentres: Rotherham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when an Equality Impact Assessment will be published on the proposal to close Goldthorpe jobcentre.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","62455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682426","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>Once a complaint has been accepted for investigation, the ICE Office will consider whether a solution to the complaint can be brokered with the relevant department or its supplier and the complainant – known as “resolution”. If it is not possible to resolve the complaint, the case papers will be requested and the case will be allocated to an Investigation Case Manager.</p><p> </p><p>Following a review of the evidence, it may be possible for the Investigation Case Manager to “settle” the complaint if the relevant department or its supplier agrees to action that satisfies the complainant. If the complaint cannot be settled, the ICE will issue a report detailing findings and any recommendations for redress.</p><p> </p><p>In the 2016 calendar year the average time taken to process complaints relating to the Child Support Agency, from the point the complaint was accepted for investigation to case closure, was 53 weeks.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Time taken to process Child Support Agency complaints during the 2016 calendar year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Less than six months</p></td><td><p>49</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>More than six months (but less than nine)</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>More than nine months (but less than 12)</p></td><td><p>76</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>More than 12 months</p></td><td><p>265</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Resources for the Independent Case Examiner’s Office are reviewed annually.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","62316 ; 62317","2017-02-07T16:04:45.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682426/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682426/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682426/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Child Support Agency: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will increase resources for the Independent Care Examiner to enable it to deal with Child Support Agency appeal cases in a timely manner.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","62433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682427","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>We have carefully considered the wider impacts on local communities when developing our proposals for Goldthorpe Jobcentre. The economic impact of employment is dispersed beyond the specific location of a workplace and the staff currently based at Goldthorpe Jobcentre already live in a broader area around the site.</p><p>While we expect all of these staff to move to Mexborough Jobcentre it is unlikely that a significant proportion will also move their place of residence. Or Proposals for Goldthorpe Jobcentre are under public consultation and we will carefully consider any further concerns raised around economic impact during the process.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T16:25:37.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682427/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682427/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682427/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Jobcentres: Rotherham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment has been made of the effect on the local economy of proposed relocation of jobs from Goldthorpe jobcentre.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","62451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682428","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>We do not anticipate any compulsory redundancies as a result of merging staff and services from Goldthorpe into Mexborough Jobcentre.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T14:38:05.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682428/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682428/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682428/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Jobcentres: Rotherham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether compulsory redundancies will result from the closure of Goldthorpe jobcentre.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","62450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682429","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Department has sought, where feasible, to merge sites in close proximity as part of its overall review of estate. Merging the staff and services from Goldthorpe into Mexborough Jobcentre optimises use of space, ensures value for money and enables effective delivery of services to the public.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T14:44:01.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682429/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682429/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Jobcentres: Rotherham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the criteria used were for the selection of Goldthorpe jobcentre for proposed closure.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","62453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682430","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>When we are informed by a receiving parent that the paying parent has missed a payment whilst on direct pay, they can request to move on to the collect and pay service. We will make this change as soon as possible unless the paying parent produces evidence that the payment was made.</p><p> </p><p>Where the paying parent is employed we will immediately attempt to deduct from their earnings with a deduction from earnings order. We have at our disposal a wide range of enforcement powers including deducting from bank accounts, seizing property, removal of driving licences and commitment to prison. Arrears accrued on direct pay can be enforced using any of our enforcement powers.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-07T16:12:33.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682430/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682430/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what powers of enforcement are available to the Child Maintenance Service if parents are on a direct-pay scheme and the paying parent refuses to meet their obligation to pay.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","62448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682431","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-08","<p>The principal aim of the child maintenance reforms is to encourage parents to work together to set up their maintenance arrangement. The free Child Maintenance Options Service provides help and support to parents to set up a collaborative arrangement either through a family based arrangement, or on the statutory scheme using Direct Pay.</p><p> </p><p>For those parents who are unable to work together, or do not meet their maintenance obligations, the Collect and Pay service is available.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-08T17:14:30.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682431/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682431/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether it is the Government's policy to encourage parents to use the Child Maintenance Services collect and pay service.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","62449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682432","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-03","<p>We are working to improve outcomes for children and believe in the importance of tackling parental conflict to achieve this. We will shortly be publishing a green paper on Social Justice that will set out our strategy for taking this work forward.</p><p> </p><p>The Department funds a range of services nationally that do good work to support families in need. Relate is one of a number of organisations funded by the Department to provide services to help reduce couple conflict and promote family stability.</p><p> </p><p>All of the organisations are subject to a ‘payment by results’ arrangement where payments are only made once we are satisfied that an agreed service has been delivered. Alongside this we also monitor the effectiveness of the service by assessing improvements in key areas such as improved conflict resolution and relationship quality. While no formal assessment is being made into impact on family stability specifically, the services currently being delivered by Relate and similar services have been shown to have a positive effect on relationship quality, wellbeing and communication.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-03T12:43:17.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682432/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682432/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Relate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment the Government has made of the (a) effectiveness of those relationship support services provided by Relate which are funded from the public purse and (b) effect of those services on family stability.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","62490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682433","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-08","<p>This Government is committed to building a country that works for everyone. That is why our forthcoming Green Paper will identify and address the root causes of child poverty, building on the new statutory indicators of parental worklessness and children’s educational attainment set out in the Welfare Reform and Work Act 2016.</p><p> </p><p>We know that work is the best route out of poverty. The Government’s welfare reforms – including the measures in that Act to increase work incentives and reduce welfare dependency – are working. We now have the lowest rate of unemployment in over a decade, and the lowest number of workless households since records began. 557,000 fewer children are now living in workless households than in 2010. There is clear evidence that good quality work is linked to better physical and mental health and improved wellbeing, and better parental health is associated with better outcomes for children.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also increasing the National Living Wage to £9 an hour by 2020, helping give lower earners their fastest pay rise in 20 years.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-08T16:47:41.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682433/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682433/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682433/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effect of the benefit freeze on trends in the level of child poverty.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","62502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682434","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-03","<p>This Department enjoys a constructive relationship with the Relationship Alliance and we engage with them frequently on a range of topics. I was fortunate to meet with Relate, along with the other members of the Relationship Alliance, on the 23 January this year. We had a productive discussion on a range of topics, including the challenges associated with tackling parental conflict at a national level. The Department has collaborated with Relate as well as a range of stakeholders to develop a new program to tackle parental conflict.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-03T10:34:36.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682434/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682434/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Relate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent representations he has received on Government funding of services by Relate; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","62491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682435","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>The claimant count for Goldthorpe is 450 of which 165 are female. This information is available from the following link: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk</a>. Figures have been rounded to the nearest 5.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p><p> </p><p>These are UC and JSA claimants served by Goldthorpe Jobcentre. We are unable to identify disabled claimants, or provide exact figures of ESA and IS claimants, however the purpose of the equality analysis is to help establish how many people are likely to be affected by the proposal.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T14:49:51.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682435/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682435/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Jobcentres: Rotherham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants are served by Goldthorpe jobcentre; and how many of those claimants are (a) disabled and (b) women.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","62454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682436","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Department published the research and statistics that formed the Review in 2016. The Review Report, which will draw together the findings from the published research and statistics, will be published in Spring this year.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-03T11:01:55.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682436/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682436/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to publish the conclusions of the review carried out under section 141 of the Welfare Reform Act 2012 on the effect of child maintenance charges; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","62417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682437","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-06","<p>Information is not available for the whole of the period requested. Information for ESA and JSA for part of the period is in the link below at Tables 1.8 and 2.6</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/jobseekers-allowance-and-employment-and-support-allowance-sanctions-decisions-made-to-june-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/jobseekers-allowance-and-employment-and-support-allowance-sanctions-decisions-made-to-june-2016</a></p><p> </p><p>Information for Universal Credit is not currently available.</p><p> </p><p>The Department published its strategy for releasing official statistics on benefit sanctions, including Universal Credit in April 2016. As outlined in the strategy, officials are currently developing the data for UC sanctions and will only release information once the necessary quality assurance work has taken place. These statistics will be published in accordance with the relevant protocols in the Code of Practice for official statistics.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-02-06T16:15:43.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682437/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682437/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many appeals against each type of benefit sanction have been (a) upheld and (b) overturned in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","62510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682438","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-08","<p>The government does not restrict Child Benefit for third and subsequent children.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-02-08T15:33:46.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682438/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682438/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682438/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-31","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on child poverty of restrictions on child benefit for third and subsequent children.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","62517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682439","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>The information as requested is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The available information on sanctions is available at:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T14:57:52.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682439/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682439/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefit sanctions have been applied to (a) employment and support allowance claimants, (b) jobseeker's allowance claimants, (c) universal credit claimants with children in each parliamentary constituency in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","62518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682440","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>The table below gives statistics on the number of planned award reviews conducted on recipients of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) for a range of conditions. Award reviews ensure that claimants continue to receive the correct level of support, including increasing support where a long-term health condition or disability deteriorates and daily living or mobility needs increase.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 – PIP award reviews</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Apr 2013 – Mar 2014</p></td><td><p>Apr 2014 – Mar 2015</p></td><td><p>Apr 2015 – Mar 2016</p></td><td><p>Apr 2016 – Oct 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Rheumatoid arthritis</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>1,200</p></td><td><p>2,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Multiple sclerosis</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>800</p></td><td><p>1,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parkinson’s disease, Parkinson's syndrome and Parkinsonism</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Motor neurone disease</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cystic fibrosis</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><ul><li>‘-’ indicates fewer than 50 cases in the category.</li><li>Data is based on primary disabling condition as recorded on the PIP and DLA computer system. Claimants may often have multiple disabling conditions upon which the decision is based but only the primary condition is shown in these statistics.</li><li>Data has been rounded to the nearest 100.</li><li>Data taken from the PIP computer system’s management information.</li><li>Figures are for Great Britain only.</li></ul><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-02-07T15:16:09.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682440/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682440/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Chronic Illnesses: Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many completed repeat assessments there have been of people with (a) Parkinson's disease, (b) multiple sclerosis, (c) motor neurone disease, (d) rheumatoid arthritis and (e) cystic fibrosis by year of repeat assessment, since the introduction of personal independence payments in 2013; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","62586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682441","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Department does not own any of the buildings within the estate, and after 20 years the leases and contracts covering many of our buildings end in March 2018. The overall requirement in DWP for processing work is reducing and we do not need the same size estate we currently have.</p><p> </p><p>Our strategic review of estate has concluded that there is no requirement for the space currently occupied in Llanelli Crown Buildings and that the work currently undertaken there can be accommodated elsewhere in the network. We have not, therefore, discussed the potential for sharing use of the space.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-03T13:12:17.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682441/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682441/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Department for Work and Pensions: Llanelli","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions he has had with other potential users of his Department's building on Llanelli on sharing the use of that space.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","62607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682442","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Department is currently completing a major renegotiation of leases, and consider that the publication now of current costs risk securing the best value for money.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-03T10:57:41.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682442/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682442/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682442/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the cost per square metre is of each office, excluding jobcentres, currently used by his Department.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","62609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682443","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>We are not yet in a position to share an estimated figure due to commercial confidentiality pending completion of legal processes and staff consultations. We expect to make savings for the tax payer from merging offices by reducing running costs and making best use of both office space available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T15:06:05.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682443/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682443/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Jobcentres: Rotherham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the expected costs are of the proposal to relocate staff and resources from Goldthorpe Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","62576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682444","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-03","<p>It is widely acknowledged that the reasons why people use food banks are complex and overlapping. It is misleading to link them to any particular cause.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s approach has been about recognising the value and importance of work, to make work pay and to support people into work whilst protecting the most vulnerable in society.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to ensuring that those in work are paid a fair wage; have opportunities to progress and achieve their potential. We are getting people into employment and working to change attitudes, introducing reforms to make sure that work always pays.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-03T13:08:37.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682444/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682444/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Food Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 9 January 2017 to Question 58293, what steps his Department is taking to end food poverty and reliance on food banks.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","62617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682445","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-03","<p>The overall requirement in DWP for processing work is reducing and we do not need the same size estate we currently have. Specifically, the work undertaken at Llanelli Crown Buildings is reducing and due to end within the next 2-3 years.</p><p> </p><p>The overall requirement for that work from March 2018 is deliverable out of fewer buildings which better match our strategic requirements and, therefore, the building in Llanelli will no longer be required.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-03T13:15:15.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682445/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682445/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-31","Department for Work and Pensions: Llanelli","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential benefits of moving additional work from elsewhere to his Department's building in Llanelli to make that site more cost effective.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","62608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682446","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Department’s main support programme for start-up businesses is the Start Up Loan programme. The following tables show the number and value of Start Up Loans issued since the programme was launched in 2012.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>(a) St Helens</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Value (£)</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>159030</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>166000</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>72961</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>117950</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>(b) Merseyside</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Value</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>14700</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2255214</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2613001</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>1266860</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>1397774</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>(c) the North West</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Value</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>74200</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>9133096</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>9698183</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>5270121</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>8633777</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>(d) England</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Value</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>740219.3</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>60752665</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>60474669</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>52193345</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>72521195</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-03T13:24:18.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682446/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682446/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-31","New Businesses: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much funding his Department has provided to start-up businesses in (a) St Helens, (b) Merseyside, (c) the North West and (d) England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","62616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682447","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-09","<p>Maintaining and building on the UK’s world-leading fusion expertise and securing alternative routes into the international fusion R&amp;D projects such as the Joint European Torus (JET) project will be a priority. Government is working closely with the UK Atomic Energy Authority on ways to achieve this.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-09T15:50:03.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682447/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682447/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682447/answer/previousversion/34089","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682447/answer/previousversion/34089","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-31","EURATOM","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect on the (a) Joint European Torus project and (b) Culham Centre for Fusion Energy of the UK's decision to withdraw from Euratom; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","62627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682448","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-09","<p>Maintaining and building on the UK’s world-leading fusion expertise and securing alternative routes into the international fusion R&amp;D projects such as the Joint European Torus (JET) project will be a priority. Government is working closely with the UK Atomic Energy Authority on ways to achieve this.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-09T15:47:25.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682448/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682448/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682448/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682448/answer/previousversion/34090","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682448/answer/previousversion/34090","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-31","EURATOM","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will make an assessment of the effect of the UK ceasing to be a member of Euratom on the Joint European Torus project's (a) funding, (b) staffing, (c) operational experiments and (d) collaboration with other EU scientist and member states.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","62628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682449","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Government is currently considering the Review’s recommendations and the issues which arise from a broader programme. Government will require a period of time to assess those issues and determine what is in the best interest of the UK energy consumer and taxpayer in the long term. The Government will publish its response to the Hendry Review in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-06T14:25:53.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682449/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682449/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682449/answer/previousversion/34087","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682449/answer/previousversion/34087","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-31","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of the recommendations in the Hendry Review on the proposed Swansea tidal lagoon and other similar projects; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","62629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682450","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-03","<p>The public consultation for the Review of the Groceries Code Adjudicator (GCA) ran from 18 October 2016 to 10 January 2017. During this period BEIS officials undertook several, widely publicised stakeholder events across the UK and met with a range of organisations and individuals to explain the purpose of the Review, how to respond and hear the views of those stakeholders who attended.</p><p>We have not been made aware of any groups who formally declined to submit evidence, but welcome the opportunity to discuss the Review more widely and would encourage such groups to contact BEIS if they would find this helpful.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-03T10:01:52.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682450/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682450/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-31","Groceries Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to meet with farming unions and industry groups who formally declined to submit evidence to the Groceries Code Adjudicator Review.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","62614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682451","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-03","<p>Civil Servants have to ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the Department’s Departmental Security Unit. Passes can also be issued to contractors, secondees and frequent visitors on a case by case basis in regards to specific business needs. Numbers of passes issued directly to non-Civil Servants for access to departmental buildings will fluctuate over the course of a year.</p><p>Civil Service Passes are underpinned by a strong physical security focus, clear processes and assurance.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-03T14:33:14.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682451/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682451/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-31","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which persons not employed by his Department and its agencies hold security passes entitling them to enter his Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682452","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Department has commissioned a study, “Assessing the cost reduction potential and competitiveness of novel (next generation) UK carbon capture technology,” to determine how the Department can support next generation carbon capture technology in future innovation programme funding and support cost reduction in carbon capture. The study will complete in autumn 2017.</p><p>In addition, the UK is a member of Mission Innovation, and participating in the Carbon Capture Innovation Challenge <sup>[</sup><sup>1] </sup>which seeks to identify breakthrough technologies and research and development opportunities in carbon capture technology with the aim of lowering costs and facilitating global carbon capture and storage deployment.</p><p>[1] <a href="http://mission-innovation.net/our-work/innovation-challenges/carbon-capture-challenge/" target="_blank">http://mission-innovation.net/our-work/innovation-challenges/carbon-capture-challenge/</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-08T15:15:18.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682452/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682452/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-31","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the commercial viability of the methods proposed by recent research and development on reducing the costs of carbon capture technology by up to two-thirds in the (a) UK and (b) rest of the world.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","62425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682453","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Department funded a twelve month £2.5 million project, led by the Energy Technologies Institute, to progress the appraisal of five selected carbon dioxide storage sites in the North and Irish Seas; three of these sites were offshore saline formations. The report, “<a href="http://www.eti.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/D16-10113ETIS-WP6-Report-Publishable-Summary.pdf" target="_blank">Progressing Development of the UK’s Strategic Carbon Dioxide Storage Resource</a>”, was published by the Energy Technologies Institute in May 2016 and is available at: <a href="http://www.eti.co.uk/project/strategic-uk-ccs-storage-appraisal/" target="_blank">http://www.eti.co.uk/project/strategic-uk-ccs-storage-appraisal/</a>.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-06T14:25:20.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682453/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682453/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682453/answer/previousversion/34082","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682453/answer/previousversion/34082","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-31","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the potential use of deep offshore saline aquifers in developing a viable business model for carbon capture and storage technology.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","62416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682454","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-06","<p>In the 2014 <em>Implementing Geological Disposal</em> White Paper Government set out three initial actions which will provide greater clarity on issues such as geology, development impacts and community representation. Good progress is being made on these initial actions and Government expects to consult on the draft National Policy Statement and Working with Communities policy in the coming months, ahead of the launch of the official siting process.</p><p>As set out in the 2014 White Paper, once the siting process has been launched any interested community will be able to initiate discussions about the possibility of becoming the host community for a geological disposal facility.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-06T14:24:09.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682454/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682454/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682454/answer/previousversion/34083","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682454/answer/previousversion/34083","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-31","Radioactive Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to invite councils to volunteer to be part of the Radioactive Waste Management search for a geological disposal facility host community.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","62478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682455","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Government is considering the recommendations in the Hendry Review and the issues which arise from a broader programme. Government will require a period of time to assess the merits of such a programme and determine what is in the best interest of the UK energy consumer and taxpayer in the long term, and will publish its response to the Hendry Review in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-08T15:16:47.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682455/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682455/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-31","Tidal Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the merits of encouraging the development of tidal lagoons to provide energy; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","62525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682456","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>In December 2013 we placed advice online to raise awareness of the key security and political risks which UK businesses may face when operating abroad, including in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories. This includes guidance on Israeli settlements. There are currently no plans to update this guidance.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-07T14:30:52.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682456/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682456/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-31","Overseas Trade: Occupied Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will publish and promote a stronger set of guidelines to businesses and banks to ensure they respect international law and human rights in their dealings with Israeli businesses operating in occupied territory.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","62461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682457","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>The UK, alongside our EU partners abstained on a vote about proposals for a database at vote at the UN Human Rights Council in March 2016 . The database has not yet been finalised.</p><p>In December 2013 we placed advice online to raise awareness of the key security and political risks which UK businesses may face when operating abroad, including in Israel and the Occupied Palestinian Territories. This includes guidance on Israeli settlements. We are advising British businesses to bear in mind the British Government's view on the illegality of settlements under international law when considering their investments and activities in the region.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-07T14:33:24.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682457/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682457/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-31","Overseas Trade: Israeli Settlements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will support measures by the UN Human Rights Council to draw up a database of all UK firms involved in trade or financial dealings with illegal settlements in coordination with the EU and UN.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","62462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682458","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-03","<p>I refer my hon. Friend to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Orkney and Shetland on the 1st of January 2017, UIN 61800; copied below:</p><p>Whisky is a major export worth £3.9 billion in 2015 and there are opportunities for future growth. We are fully engaged with the Scotch Whisky Association and are working to maintain access to current markets and open new ones through a range of tools to strengthen our trade relationships.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-02-03T13:43:44.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682458/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682458/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-31","Whisky: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on potential increases in the amount of Scotch whisky exported.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","62487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682459","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-08","<p>DIT’s trade promotion staff in South Africa support commercial activity between the UK and South Africa across a number of sectors, including mining. In addition UK Export Finance welcomes applications from the mining sector for support to export to South Africa.</p><p>DIT staff regularly meet and work with UK companies in the mining industry. In addition, DIT hosts British companies in a UK Pavilion at the annual Mining Indaba in Cape Town - the most important commercial event in the African mining industry calendar. This year, 19 companies will be represented and have direct access to support from DIT staff.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-08T15:24:25.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682459/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682459/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-31","Overseas Trade: South Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps the Government is taking to strengthen the mining trade between the UK and South Africa.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","62630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682460","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-08","<p>The latest data on UK trade in oil products with Libya are given in Table 1 below:</p><p><strong>Table 1: UK trade in oil products with Libya </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>UK exports of oil products (HS 27) to Libya</p></td><td><p>UK imports of oil products (HS 27) from Libya</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2015 to November 2016</p></td><td><p>£186,344</p></td><td><p>£196,899,814</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Source: HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) Overseas Trade Statistics database</strong></p><p><strong>Note: Oil products defined as HS code 27: Mineral fuels, mineral oils and products of their distillation; bituminous substances; mineral waxes</strong></p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-08T15:25:55.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682460/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682460/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-31","Libya: Oil","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what information he holds on receipts and revenue flows accruing to the regimes in Libya from oil exports in the most recent period for which figures are available; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","62594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682461","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) staff along with all civil servants have the ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. At present, DIT operate in shared buildings where it is not the major tenant. The responsibility of issuing passes does not fall directly to DIT but to the local Departmental Security teams responsible for the building.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-08T15:27:23.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682461/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682461/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-31","Department for International Trade: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, which persons not employed by his Department hold security passes entitling them to enter his Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682462","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-08","<p>Civil servants have to have the ability to work flexibly across government sites where there is a business need to do so. The issuing of all passes is controlled by the local Departmental Security teams. Passes can also be issued to contractors or secondees based within Government premises on a case by case basis in regards to specific business needs. Numbers of passes issued directly to non-civil servants for access to departmental buildings will fluctuate over the course of a year.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-08T14:52:52.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682462/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682462/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-31","Department for Exiting the European Union: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, which persons not employed by his Department hold security passes entitling them to enter his Department's premises.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682465","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-07","<p>DExEU is accommodated in Cabinet Office and Ministry of Defence buildings and I refer to the answers given by my honourable friends, the Member for Ipswich (Ben Gummer) on 07 February 2017 and Member for Milton Keynes North (Mark Lancaster) on 02 February 2017.<br><br></p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-07T17:38:29.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682465/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682465/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-31","Department for Exiting the European Union: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, at what hourly rate cleaners are paid by his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","62496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682466","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is committed to ensuring staff maintain a work-life balance. The department has flexible working policies in place to facilitate this to avoid excess working hours. All overtime is pre-agreed with line managers with 48 hours notice and is managed locally so no central records are held.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","62495","2017-02-08T14:45:55.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682466/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682466/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-31","Department for Exiting the European Union: Overtime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what systems are in place to monitor overtime worked by his Department's employees.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","62497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682467","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-08","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is committed to ensuring staff maintain a work-life balance. The department has flexible working policies in place to facilitate this to avoid excess working hours. All overtime is pre-agreed with line managers with 48 hours notice and is managed locally so no central records are held.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","62497","2017-02-08T14:45:55.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682467/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682467/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-31","Department for Exiting the European Union: Overtime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many hours of recorded overtime have been worked by staff in his Department since its creation.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","62495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682468","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-08","<p>All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK. As recruitment is ongoing we will not be giving a running commentary. The overall size and scope of the new department, including staffing, is regularly reviewed. We will ensure we are appropriately staffed to deal with the task at hand. The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 300 staff.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-08T14:40:16.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682468/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/682468/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-31","Department for Exiting the European Union: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 25 January 2017 to Question 60441, approximately how many more staff he needs to recruit to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","62434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685135","Department for Education","false","2017-02-06","<p>Good teachers are critical to improving educational outcomes. We are supporting the professional development of teachers – including through the publication of the Professional Development Standard and the new Teaching and Leadership Innovation Fund – and removing unnecessary workload. Schools have increased flexibilities, enabling Heads to attract the best teachers and focus on delivering an outstanding education for all their pupils.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-06T17:26:36.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685135/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685135/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-31","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to support teachers in improving educational outcomes.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","908608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685136","Department for Education","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Skills Funding Agency manages providers and course eligibility for Advanced Learner Loans. The Student Loans Company administers these loans, which fund learners’ course fees.</p><p>Both have robust procedures should there be an exceptional need to transfer loans-funded learners to a different provider. Contact is made with learners to inform them of the situation, as well as the options available to them. All efforts are made to minimise the level of disruption during any transition.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-02-06T16:52:57.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685136/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685136/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-31","Further Education: Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will provide support to people who incur debt owed to the Skills Funding Agency as a result of training providers ceasing to operate.","false","Biography information for Karin Smyth","Bristol South","Karin Smyth","908603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685137","Department for Education","false","2017-02-06","<p>The government is committed to raising standards in primary mathematics teaching.</p><p>We have established Maths Hubs - 35 school-led centres of excellence with a role in leading transformation of teaching based on best practice internationally. We are investing £41m to enable primary schools to introduce highly effective south-east Asian mastery teaching methods.</p><p>We are also investing in primary mathematics initial teacher training (ITT) courses, to allow trainee primary teachers to specialise in the subject.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-06T17:24:31.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685137/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685137/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-31","Mathematics: Primary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps the Government is taking to improve the quality of maths teaching in primary schools.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bingham","High Peak","Andrew Bingham","908610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685138","Department for Education","false","2017-02-06","<p>We are committed to 3 million more apprenticeships, which are for people of all ages and creating new technical education routes. Delivered by a revitalised FE sector, including specialist institutions, these will provide people with the skills employers need.</p><p>We are also supporting adults to retrain through advanced learner loans and we will be exploring ambitious new approaches to encourage lifetime learning, including in HE which has a role extending opportunities for adults.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-02-06T16:51:03.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685138/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/685138/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-31","Adult Education and Lifelong Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans she has to increase provision for adult skills and lifelong learning.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","908600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680939","Home Office","false","2017-02-09","<p>In 2016, we transferred over 900 unaccompanied minors to the UK from Europe, including more than 750 from France as part of the UK’s support for the Calais camp clearance. Many have been reunited with family members already in the UK, while others are being cared for by local authorities across the UK.</p><p>The primary responsibility for unaccompanied children in Europe lies with the State in which they are present. The Government has established a £10 million Refugee Children Fund for Europe to support the needs of vulnerable refugee and migrant children arriving in Europe. We have also created a Child Trafficking Protection Fund of up to £3m, which seeks to fund work at a local, regional or national level, adding value to the existing provisions for child victims of modern slavery, including trafficking. The fund will help victim support and recovery, which might include specialist care to trafficked children. It will also reduce vulnerability to exploitation, for example by tackling the problem of trafficked children going missing after identification in the UK, and possibly being re-trafficked.</p><p>My honourable Friend, Robert Goodwill’s joint Written Ministerial Statement with Edward Timpson on 1 November committed the Government to publishing a strategy for the safeguarding of unaccompanied asylum-seeking and refugee children in England; and the children who have been identified for transfer from Europe.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-09T14:07:59.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680939/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680939/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 25 January (HL Deb, col 665–6), what assessment they have made of whether refugee children who have been reported as having gone missing are likely to have become victims of human trafficking and exploitation; and what measures they and their European partners have taken to protect such children.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL5065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680940","Home Office","false","2017-02-13","<p>The UK has committed significant resources to helping the EU deal with the migration crisis, including seconding staff to Europol.</p><p> </p><p>The UK government recognises the vital role Europol has to play in coordinating law enforcement activity against migration related criminality. The National Crime Agency (NCA) and Immigration Enforcement second staff to Europol to work on these issues specifically, including within the European Migrant Smuggling Centre (EMSC). The UK continues to encourage international partners to share relevant information with Europol, supporting the EMSC's aim of strengthening support for EU Member States through enhanced intelligence exchange.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to the support we give to Europol, the Government has established a £10 million Refugee Children Fund for Europe to support the needs of vulnerable refugee and migrant children arriving in Europe. The UK is the largest bilateral contributor to the humanitarian response to the crisis in Europe and the Balkans with a total allocation of £70 million.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-13T14:22:18.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680940/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680940/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 25 January (HL Deb, cols 665–6) what support they have given to Europol in determining the fate of the 10,000 refugee children whom Europol reported in January as having gone missing.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL5066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680941","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-07","<p>Following the meeting between the UK Special Envoy to Sudan and South Sudan and the Sudanese Foreign Minister, Ibrahim Ghandour, the Minister has reconfirmed the government of Sudan’s commitment to improving humanitarian access to the two areas of Blue Nile and South Kordofan. We continue to encourage the Sudan People’s Liberation Movement-North (SPLM-N) to agree to proposals to guarantee direct medical support to the areas under their control as a way to unblock a broader agreement on longer term access.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-02-07T16:28:45.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680941/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680941/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680941/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Sudan: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of progress towards full humanitarian access to the Blue Nile and South Kordofan states following the meeting between of the UK Special Envoy to Sudan and South Sudan and the Sudanese Foreign Minister on 24 January.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL5067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680942","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>The UK Special Representative for Sudan and South Sudan and the Sudanese Foreign Minister Ibrahim Ghandour discussed the political process outlined in the African Union Roadmap agreement, including the need for inclusivity in Sudan’s national dialogue, which was designed to be open to all political parties, civil society and rebel groups. The UK Special Representative also raised our concerns about the detention of human rights defenders, civil society activists and members of the political opposition directly with the Foreign Minister.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL5069","2017-02-08T15:35:45.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680942/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680942/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680942/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Sudan: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations the UK Special Envoy to Sudan and South Sudan made to the Sudanese Foreign Minister regarding the environment for civil society activists in Sudan at their meeting on 24 January.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL5068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680943","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>The UK Special Representative for Sudan and South Sudan and the Sudanese Foreign Minister Ibrahim Ghandour discussed the political process outlined in the African Union Roadmap agreement, including the need for inclusivity in Sudan’s national dialogue, which was designed to be open to all political parties, civil society and rebel groups. The UK Special Representative also raised our concerns about the detention of human rights defenders, civil society activists and members of the political opposition directly with the Foreign Minister.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL5068","2017-02-08T15:35:45.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680943/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680943/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Sudan: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations the UK Special Envoy to Sudan and South Sudan made to the Sudanese Foreign Minister regarding the case for an inclusive national dialogue process at their meeting on 24 January.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL5069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680944","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>Our Embassy in Khartoum will facilitate these events by providing business links and advice to the Middle East Association’s commercial mission. The Government is not providing any financial support. More widely, we will continue to provide support to UK companies to understand the opportunities and challenges of operating in Sudan.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-08T15:33:36.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680944/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680944/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Sudan: Trade Promotion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 23 January (HL Deb, col 425) concerning recent developments in Sudan, whether they are providing any support to (1) the British commercial mission that will visit Khartoum in April, and (2) a seminar focusing on the promotion of British business to be held in Khartoum in February.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL5070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680945","Attorney General","false","2017-02-13","<p>Victims of domestic abuse can challenge a CPS decision not to prosecute their case, under the Victims’ Right to Review (VRR) scheme. In 2015-16, the CPS made 41,503 decisions in domestic abuse cases. 520 of these cases were appealed through the VRR scheme; 49 of which were upheld. Of the total number of domestic abuse decisions, the upheld rate was 0.12%. Of the number of domestic abuse VRR appeals, the upheld rate was 9.4%. An inquiry is not required because these volumes and proportions are small and the CPS is, in the majority of domestic abuse cases, accurate in its decision making.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-13T14:24:37.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680945/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680945/answer",,,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-01-30","Domestic Abuse: Prosecutions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of cases in which the Crown Prosecution Service’s (CPS's) decisions not to initiate prosecutions in cases of domestic violence have been successfully challenged, whether they will commission an inquiry into the policy and practice of the CPS in relation to that issue.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL5071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680946","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-09","<p>We have made clear that, outcomes for children in custody are not good enough. This is evident for all young offenders, including those who identify as Gypsy, Roma and Traveller (GRT).</p><p> </p><p>It is noteworthy, however, that in the 2015/16 ‘Children in Custody’ report that describes the number of GRT children in young offender institutions (YOI), that participation in education, work or vocational or skills training in custody is higher for those identifying as GRT in YOIs when compared to the rest of the cohort.</p><p> </p><p>In December we set out our response to Charlie Taylor’s review of the youth justice system and how we will improve outcomes for young people across the youth custodial estate. Measures include developing a new pre-apprenticeship pathway to ensure that all children and young people are in education, training or employment on their release, boosting the number of front line staff in YOIs and developing two ‘secure schools’ with a particular focus on education and health.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Youth Justice Board (YJB) is keen in principle to move to the 18+1 ethnicity monitoring system from the 2011 Census and is examining the requirements and dependencies with existing IT systems and identifying the feasibility and indicative costs of moving to the revised classification system.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-09T15:44:19.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680946/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680946/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Youth Justice: Travellers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the recommendations by the Traveller Movement in its report <i>Overlooked and Overrepresented: Gypsy, Traveller and Roma children in the youth justice system, </i>to address the poorer outcomes for Gypsy, Traveller and Roma children in youth justice, and in particular the case for the Youth Justice Board to update its ethnicity data collection system to include Gypsy and Traveller categories.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL5072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680947","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-13","<p>We want all children in custody to be fully occupied in education and training throughout the day with a core curriculum focussed on preparing them for employment, an apprenticeship or continued education when they are resettled back into their communities. As part of our reforms we will ensure governors have increased flexibility to work with providers to decide how education is best delivered to meet the different needs of the young people in their establishments.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-13T14:26:04.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680947/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680947/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680947/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Young Offenders: Travellers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will consider targeted education and vocational skills interventions for Gypsy, Traveller and Roma children in youth custody in the light of the Traveller Movement’s finding in <i>Overlooked and Overrepresented: Gypsy, Traveller and Roma children in the youth justice system </i>that 55 per cent of Gypsy, Traveller and Roma children in Secure Training Centres had learnt skills for jobs they would like to do in the future.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL5073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680948","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-09","<p>We have already introduced elements from the models used in the adult estate in Young Offender Institutions (YOIs). These include guidance on good practice, which is available to all staff and includes guidance on those identifying as Gypsy, Romany or Traveller (GRT); and issues for the management of GRT young people which is incorporated into the general training of new officers.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to improving the outcomes for all young people in the youth justice system, including those who identify as GRT. We want all young people in custody to have their individual needs assessed and a personal plan in place to drive improvements in their behaviour, education and health.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-09T15:43:33.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680948/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680948/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Young Offenders: Travellers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration has been given to establishing and promoting Gypsy, Traveller and Roma groups in Secure Training Centres and Young Offenders Institutions, based on successful models seen in the secure adult estate.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL5074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680949","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-13","<p>Following a letter received from the National Police Chief’s Council lead for Gypsy, Roma and Traveller issues, in December we responded by acknowledging their interest and to confirm that the Youth Justice Board (YJB) are keen in principle to move to the 18+1 ethnicity monitoring system from the 2011 Census.</p><p> </p><p>The YJB is examining the requirements and dependencies with existing IT systems and identifying the feasibility and indicative costs of moving to the revised classification system.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-13T16:39:03.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680949/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680949/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Youth Justice: Ethnic Groups","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have consulted, or had representations from, the National Police Chiefs’ Council on the merits of updating the ethnicity data collection used in the youth justice system to include the 2011 Census ethnic group classifications.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL5075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680950","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The new Drug Strategy will be published soon.</p><p> </p><p>We are developing our new Drug Strategy, which will build on work to date to prevent drug use in our communities and help dependent individuals to recover, working across Government and with key partners, including commissioners, treatment providers, service users and our independent experts, the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs, to identify what further steps we can take to tackle this issue<strong>.</strong></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL5078","2017-02-02T16:55:08.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680950/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680950/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Drugs: Misuse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to publish their new drugs strategy.","false","Biography information for Lord Carlile of Berriew",,"Lord Carlile of Berriew","HL5076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680951","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>There are no plans to review the role, duty and constitution of the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs (ACMD) as set out in the Misuse of Drugs Act 1971.</p><p> </p><p>The budgets for the ACMD are reviewed annually as part of the Home Office business planning round. There are no current plans to change significantly the ACMD budget from current levels although we will continue to ensure the service is value for money in future.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office expects to begin an appointment round for the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs in 2017 in line with Cabinet Office’s Governance Code on Public Appointments.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-02T16:55:36.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680951/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680951/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any proposals to change the terms of reference, budget or membership of the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs.","false","Biography information for Lord Carlile of Berriew",,"Lord Carlile of Berriew","HL5077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680952","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The new Drug Strategy will be published soon.</p><p> </p><p>We are developing our new Drug Strategy, which will build on work to date to prevent drug use in our communities and help dependent individuals to recover, working across Government and with key partners, including commissioners, treatment providers, service users and our independent experts, the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs, to identify what further steps we can take to tackle this issue<strong>.</strong></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL5076","2017-02-02T16:55:08.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680952/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680952/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Drugs: Misuse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government who will be consulted in relation to the forthcoming new drugs strategy.","false","Biography information for Lord Carlile of Berriew",,"Lord Carlile of Berriew","HL5078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680953","Department of Health","false","2017-02-09","<p>NHS England are responsible, through local procurement exercises, for commissioning integrated substance misuse services across the secure and detained estate for both adults and young people under 18.</p><p>NHS England do not hold the information requested centrally.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-02-09T17:50:35.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680953/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680953/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Prisons: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which prisons and youth custody sites provided new services in 2016 to deal with substance misuse.","false","Biography information for Lord Carlile of Berriew",,"Lord Carlile of Berriew","HL5079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680955","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-13","<p>There has been a reduction in the number of Eritrean nationals seeking asylum in the UK. Between January-September 2016, the number was 796, a 68% decline in applications compared with the same period in 2015 when the figure was 2807. There has also been a fall of about 50% in the number of Eritreans arriving in Italy.</p><p>Tackling illegal migration to the EU from the Horn of Africa is a priority. The UK is engaging on this bilaterally, and in collaboration with international partners within the frameworks of the Khartoum Process and the EU Trust Fund. In addition, the UK is working to address the underlying causes of migration from Eritrea, including by supporting projects to promote professional development and employment opportunities to young Eritreans, and a programme to enhance judicial capacity and promote the rule of law.</p><p>Within Eritrea, only four traditional religious organisations (Orthodox Christian, Sunni Muslim, Catholic, and the Lutheran Evangelical Church of Eritrea) have official approval to operate. We are aware of reports that a number of individuals from non-sanctioned religions remain in detention, including 54 Jehovah's Witnesses, although reliable information is very difficult to obtain. Details of their detention have not been publicly released by the Eritrean government. Our Ambassador and EU counterparts have called for the release of all prisoners detained for religious beliefs or, as a minimum, that they are brought before a court for public hearing and fair trial, allowing them to defend themselves against any charge. We continue to press the government of Eritrea for specific details of their detention and health status.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-13T14:28:48.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680955/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680955/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Eritrea: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they and neighbouring states are making in stemming the exodus of people from Eritrea; and what plans they have to secure the release of the reported large numbers of persons imprisoned for religious reasons.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680956","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>My statement announced publication of guidance on Overseas Security and Justice Assistance precisely because this Government is determined never to provide assistance in a way which ignores, condones or enables torture. The guidance requires those managing any Government security or justice assistance to identify risks that their work may, even inadvertently, cause or encourage torture. Where any such risks are found to exist, they must first be mitigated and then referred up to senior officials and, where the risk is judged to be high, to Ministers for approval. We emphatically reject torture as both illegal and repugnant. The prevention of torture has long been a government priority.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-08T15:36:42.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680956/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680956/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Inhuman Treatment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Statement by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 26 January (HL WS444), whether they will take steps to ensure that such assistance does not ignore or condone the use of torture or inhuman treatment on detainees and prisoners, in particular in Turkey, Saudi Arabia and the Gulf States.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680957","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-13","<p>At the 2016 Supporting Syria and the Region Conference, donors pledged $6 billion grants for 2016 and a further $6.1 billion for 2017-2020. The Department for International Development has set up a tracking mechanism that reports on the delivery of all the financial commitments made at the Conference.</p><p>The most recent tracking report was published on 6 February 2017. It shows that of the $6 billion grants pledged for 2016, donors have spent $6.2 billion. We expect donors to fully spend their 2017-20 pledges by 2020 and continue to work with other London Conference co-hosts to urge donors to mobilise financial support to the crisis.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-02-13T16:10:35.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680957/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680957/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proportion of the $12 billion pledged in February 2016 at the Supporting Syria and the Region Conference has so far been paid; and when they expect the full payment to be made.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680958","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>Twelve MPs from the Peoples' Democratic Party (Halk Demokratik Partisi) are currently in detention in Turkey. They include the two co-leaders, who are on trial but have not yet been sentenced. Ministers have raised the issue of human rights and the rule of law in meetings with their Turkish counter-parts.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-08T15:37:18.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680958/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680958/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Turkey: Political Prisoners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many elected members of the Grand National Assembly of Turkey are now detained or imprisoned; and what discussions they have had with the government of Turkey about the sentences imposed on the leaders of the Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP).","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680959","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-09","<p>The value of UK defence export orders to Turkey for 2015, as included in the 2015 Official Defence and Security Export Statistics, was £11 million. The figures for 2016 will be released in due course.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for International Trade does not hold information on outstanding forward contracts.</p>",,"Lord Price",,"2017-02-09T14:03:54.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680959/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680959/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","Turkey: Arms Trade","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the value of British sales to Turkey of weapons and military equipment in (1) 2015, and (2) 2016; and how many forward contracts are outstanding.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680960","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>We welcome the signing of an agreement to revive the Joint Israel Palestine Water Committee for the West Bank. If fully implemented, this agreement would be an important step toward preserving the two-state solution. We encourage further cooperation between Israel and the Palestinian Authority. This is critical to the viability of a future Palestinian state.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-08T15:37:49.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680960/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680960/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","West Bank: Water","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will formally welcome the re-establishment of a joint Israel Palestine Water Committee for the West Bank; and what assessment they have made of this as a model for co-operation in the absence of any other peace process.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680961","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-13","<p>The full implications of the reinstated and expanded Mexico City policy are not yet clear but we are closely following developments. DFID will consider the implications with our offices, with UK civil society and with donors.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-02-13T15:41:03.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680961/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680961/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Developing Countries: Abortion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of the US following President Trump's reinstatement of the global gag rule; and what assessment they have made of the effect of this on the work of the Department for International Development and British development aid organisations working with women seeking assistance with, or advice on, abortion.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL5086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680962","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The UK has been a strong and consistent advocate for free and fair elections in Guyana. We, and colleagues from other diplomatic missions and international organisations, closely monitored the run-up to, and conduct of, the general election in May 2015 and local elections in March 2016. Both were deemed free and fair. The process for selecting the new head of the Election Commission is clearly laid out in the Guyanese Constitution and the President is currently following that process. The British High Commissioner in Georgetown maintains a regular dialogue with the Government of Guyana at the highest level, including on issues such as the rule of law, good governance and tackling corruption, all of which are high priorities for the UK.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-06T17:56:37.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680962/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680962/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Guyana: Elections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Guyana about the conduct of elections there, in particular regarding the case for an independent head of their Elections Commission.","false","Biography information for Baroness Northover",,"Baroness Northover","HL5087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680963","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>In 2016, we transferred over 900 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children to the UK from Europe. More children will be transferred under the Immigration Act and we will continue to meet our obligations under the Dublin Regulation. We have a long standing secondee in Italy who is based in the Italian Dublin Unit. We will announce in due course the process and criteria for transferring more children to the UK from Europe.</p><p>We continue to work with the Italian authorities to implement section 67 of the Immigration Act, and Immigration Minister met with his counterpart in November to discuss how we can support them; discussions are ongoing. We must secure the consent and cooperation of the host governments concerned before taking any action on their territory and can only act within their laws.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-02T16:58:44.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680963/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680963/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why only three of the 25,800 unaccompanied children reported by Unicef to be in Italy have been transferred to the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sheehan",,"Baroness Sheehan","HL5088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680964","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-13","<p>The UK supports Palestinian refugees affected by the Syria crisis through the United Nations Relief and Works Agency (UNRWA). This includes those who have fled to Jordan and Lebanon, as well as those displaced inside Syria. As part of DFID’s Syria Crisis Response, we have provided £79.8 million to UNRWA’s Syria Regional Emergency Appeals. In 2015 DFID’s funding to UNRWA provided food assistance every 3 months to over 67,000 people inside Syria, and over 4,000 in neighbouring countries. Our support also facilitated over 150,000 visits to primary health care services inside Syria, and more than 15,000 visits in Jordan and Lebanon. UNRWA continues to meet immediate needs through a range of programmes, including the delivery of essential relief items such as blankets, clothing, and cooking equipment.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-02-13T16:09:39.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680964/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680964/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Palestinians: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assistance they are providing to the 560,000 Palestinian refugees who have been displaced by the crisis in Syria.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680965","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>The violence and instability in Lebanon's 12 Palestine refugee camps remain areas of concern for the UK. The violence that took place in Ein El Hilweh on 15 January was an appalling demonstration of the severe difficulties that affect daily life in the camp for both the civilian population and United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees (UNRWA) staff members. The UK values UNRWA's commitment to the welfare and development of Palestinian refugees, and the impact of violence on the safety of UNRWA staff members and their ability to deliver UNRWA services continues to alarm us. Although it is not the UK's position to routinely raise specific camp security incidents with the Government of Lebanon, Palestinian refugee issues are monitored closely and raised in our regular discussions with the Lebanese Government.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-08T15:43:09.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680965/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680965/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Lebanon: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Lebanon regarding reports of alleged violence against UNRWA staff and the civilian population of Ein El Hilweh Palestine Refugee camp on 15 January.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680966","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>While we have not raised this specific issue, we have consistently urged the Israeli Government to ease movement and access restrictions in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs), most recently on 5 December. We are also supporting the UN Access Coordination Unit to work with the Israeli Government, Palestinian Authority and aid agencies to help facilitate humanitarian access in the OPTs.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-08T15:43:58.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680966/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680966/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel regarding reports of the death of a 17 year-old who was denied a permit to exit Gaza to receive lifesaving medical treatment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680967","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-13","<p>The Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) and President Trump discussed a range of foreign policy issues during their meeting on 27 January. The UK's position on the location of our embassy has not changed.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-13T14:29:31.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680967/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680967/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Israel: USA","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions the Prime Minister had during her recent meeting with President Trump regarding the proposed US embassy move to Jerusalem.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680968","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>While we have not raised this issue with the Israeli authorities, the Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr Ellwood) issued a statement on 24 January regarding the announcement of plans to build 566 new settlement homes in East Jerusalem. The Minister also raised the issue of settlements with the Israeli Deputy Foreign Minister when they spoke on 10 January 2017.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-08T15:44:54.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680968/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680968/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Israeli Settlements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel in regard to that government's announcement that a further 600 Jewish settler homes will be built in East Jerusalem.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680969","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-08","<p>While we have not raised this issue with the Israeli authorities, our Embassy in Tel Aviv has previously raised our concerns on demolitions and has repeatedly urged the Israeli authorities to provide a legal route for Palestinians to obtain building permits.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK's position on demolitions in the Occupied Palestinian Territories is clear: demolitions cause unnecessary suffering to ordinary Palestinians; are harmful to the peace process; and are, in all but the most exceptional of cases, contrary to international humanitarian law. The Fourth Geneva Convention is clear that the destruction of any real or personal property in Occupied Territory is not justified unless it is rendered absolutely necessary by military operations.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-02-08T15:48:09.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680969/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680969/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel following reports that Israel’s High Court of Justice has decided to allow the Civil Administration in the occupied West Bank to demolish eight Palestinian villages in the South Hebron Hills affecting around 1,500 Palestinians.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL5094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680970","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-13","<p>Where capacity margins narrow beyond a pre-determined threshold, automated Capacity Market Notices are issued to the market providing 4 hours advance notice that additional capacity may be required.</p><p>Before bidding into the Capacity Market, participants must ensure they would be able to meet all the obligations that would fall to them in the event of successfully securing a Capacity Market agreement. Failure to fulfil these obligations during a stress event would result in clear and pre-determined penalties.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-13T14:25:22.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680970/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680970/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","Power Stations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of their reported plans to subsidise power stations which provide guaranteed emergency electricity supply when needed on winter weekday evenings, what estimate they have made of the length of time it will take coal and nuclear power stations to reach guaranteed output capacity; and how much notice these power stations will be given of the additional demand.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL5095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680971","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-14","<p>Maintaining the UK’s ability to trade in nuclear materials and equipment will be a key objective in negotiations to allow the uninterrupted progress of the UK’s nuclear programme, which includes existing and planned nuclear power stations. Those negotiations have not yet started, but officials and Ministers are in regular contact with industry stakeholders and will continue to work closely with them as the negotiations progress.</p><p>The Government remains committed to the highest standards of nuclear safety, safeguards and support for the industry, and the Office for Nuclear Regulation will continue to be the independent regulator for the civil nuclear sector.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-02-14T15:43:27.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680971/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680971/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","EURATOM","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what will be the effect of the Government's decision to leave Euratom on the cost, safety and regulatory processes associated with existing and planned nuclear power stations.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL5096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680972","Department for Education","false","2017-02-08","<p>In our response to the Committee in July 2016, the Government committed to a range of actions designed to improve the lives and experiences of transgender people.</p><p>This included a commitment to publish an update of the LGB&amp;T Action Plan and the Transgender Action Plan and to publish a new plan on transgender equality.</p><p>We will provide an update on the Government’s progress in 2017.</p>",,"Lord Nash","HL5098","2017-02-08T14:20:37.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680972/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680972/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Gender Recognition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will publish the new transgender strategy as agreed to in the government response to recommendation 1 of the House of Commons Women and Equalities Committee 2016 Report <i>Transgender Equality</i> HC390.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull",,"Baroness Burt of Solihull","HL5097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680973","Department for Education","false","2017-02-08","<p>In our response to the Committee in July 2016, the Government committed to a range of actions designed to improve the lives and experiences of transgender people.</p><p>This included a commitment to publish an update of the LGB&amp;T Action Plan and the Transgender Action Plan and to publish a new plan on transgender equality.</p><p>We will provide an update on the Government’s progress in 2017.</p>",,"Lord Nash","HL5097","2017-02-08T14:20:37.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680973/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680973/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Gender Recognition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will publish the balance sheet of the previous transgender action plan as committed to in the government response to the Women and Equalities Committee 2016 Report HC390.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull",,"Baroness Burt of Solihull","HL5098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680974","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The report was sent to the Home Secretary on 12 December 2016. The Home Office aims to publish all ICI reports within 8 weeks of receiving them.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-02T16:55:52.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680974/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680974/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Slavery","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to publish the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration’s inspection of Border Force’s identification and treatment of potential victims of modern slavery.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hamwee",,"Baroness Hamwee","HL5099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680975","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Law Commission expects to publish its report on technical issues in charity law, together with a draft bill, this summer. The Government will need to consider the report and its recommendations carefully.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2017-02-09T14:53:54.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680975/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680975/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-30","Charities: Regulation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to introduce the Law Commission Bill on Charity Regulation.","false","Biography information for Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts",,"Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts","HL5100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680976","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-09","<p>I have written to the Honourable Lady to clarify the response I gave on 24 January; a copy has been placed in the library.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-02-09T16:12:50.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680976/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680976/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Social Mobility Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answers by Lord Henley on 24 January (HL Deb, cols 547–9), what responsibilities the Social Mobility Commission retains for the issue of child poverty since that issue was removed from its title and explicit remit by the Welfare Reform and Work Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL5101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680977","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-09","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is leading cross-government work to develop our forthcoming green paper on social justice. This will set out the Government’s approach to tackling child poverty and disadvantage and involves a wide range of policy and analytical staff from a number of key Departments including the Department for Education, the Department for Communities and Local Government and the Department of Health. Many of these staff work flexibly, dependant on work flows, and as a result we are unable to provide an FTE figure.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-02-09T17:48:05.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680977/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680977/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680977/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Child Poverty Unit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Child Poverty Unit continues to exist as a separate identifiable unit since its transfer to the Department for Work and Pensions; if so, how many full-time equivalent (FTE) staff are employed in the Unit; and if not, how many FTE staff have responsibility for child poverty within the Department.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL5102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680978","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-13","<p>The government is committed to improving the family justice system so separating couples can achieve the best possible outcomes for themselves and their families. Whilst we have no current plans to change the existing law on divorce, we are considering what further reforms to the family justice system may be needed.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-13T16:38:17.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680978/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680978/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680978/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Divorce","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to review the fault-based divorce system.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL5103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680979","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-13","<p>Individuals who are not parties in family law cases may apply to the court for disclosure of information that mentions them by name. Disclosure of such information is at the court’s discretion.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-13T14:26:30.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680979/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680979/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680979/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Family Proceedings","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to put in place a legislative procedure to enable individuals who are not parties in family law cases to have access to information that mentions them by name.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL5104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680980","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-06","<p>The fault with the gas boosters to the boiler supplying central heating and hot water at Wellington Barracks was identified on Monday 23 January 2017 and restored to working order on Thursday 26 January 2017. Electric heaters and mobile hand washing stations were provided in the intervening period.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-06T17:19:09.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680980/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680980/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680980/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-30","Wellington Barracks","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how long the central heating and hot water systems at Wellington Barracks have been out of order; and when they expect them to be restored to working order.","false","Biography information for Lord Trefgarne",,"Lord Trefgarne","HL5105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680981","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-13","<p>The Ministry of Defence Equipment Plan 2016-26 includes contingency funding of £5.25 billion. This is in addition to specific risk provision within individual project budgets of approximately £11 billion.</p><p> </p><p>Due to project costings regularly being updated the total amount of contingency is variable.</p><p> </p><p>I am withholding information relating to the use of contingency funds as its disclosure would prejudice commercial interests.</p><p> </p><p>We judge the contingency sufficient to deal with cost growth within the equipment plan and broader risks that may emerge.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-02-13T16:12:17.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680981/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680981/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680981/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-30","Defence Equipment: Procurement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the latest Ministry of Defence annual equipment plan has left the £5.8 billion contingency funding untouched.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL5106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680982","Home Office","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Code of Practice for Official Statistics has established common standards to ensure a coherent and trustworthy service to the user of statistics.</p><p><br> Home Office officials are continuing to review and assess information on the number of people claiming asylum where sexual orientation may form the basis of the claim, in order to ensure that any statistics produced meet the principles on both assured methodology and quality (ensuring statistical methods are consistent with scientific principles) and governing user needs.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-03T11:35:58.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680982/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680982/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680982/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Asylum: Russia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many LGBT asylum seekers from Russia have been held in UK detention centres in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL5107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680983","Home Office","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Code of Practice for Official Statistics has established common standards to ensure a coherent and trustworthy service to the user of statistics.</p><p><br> Home Office officials are continuing to review and assess information on the number of people claiming asylum where sexual orientation may form the basis of the claim, in order to ensure that any statistics produced meet the principles on both assured methodology and quality (ensuring statistical methods are consistent with scientific principles) and governing user needs.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-03T11:36:06.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680983/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680983/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680983/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Asylum: Russia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the average length of detention of LGBT people seeking asylum from Russia in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL5108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680984","Home Office","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Code of Practice for Official Statistics has established common standards to ensure a coherent and trustworthy service to the user of statistics.</p><p><br> Home Office officials are continuing to review and assess information on the number of people claiming asylum where sexual orientation may form the basis of the claim, in order to ensure that any statistics produced meet the principles on both assured methodology and quality (ensuring statistical methods are consistent with scientific principles) and governing user needs.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-03T11:36:12.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680984/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680984/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680984/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Asylum: Russia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many LGBT people seeking asylum from Russia have been refused leave to remain in the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL5109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680985","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Code of Practice for Official Statistics has established common standards to ensure a coherent and trustworthy service to the user of statistics.</p><p><br> Home Office officials are continuing to review and assess information on the number of people claiming asylum where sexual orientation may form the basis of the claim, in order to ensure that any statistics produced meet the principles on both assured methodology and quality (ensuring statistical methods are consistent with scientific principles) and governing user needs.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-02-02T18:00:27.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680985/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680985/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680985/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Asylum: Russia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many LGBT people seeking asylum have been deported to Russia.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL5110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680986","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>The terms of reference for the Office of Tax Simplification’s current VAT General Simplification Review are on gov.uk.</p><p> </p><p>While the Government keeps all taxes under review, a fixed proportion of each class of NICs receipts (from employees, the self-employed and employers) is allocated directly to the NHS; this adds up to about 20% of NICs receipts. The rest of NHS funding comes from general taxation.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-13T15:24:58.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680986/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680986/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680986/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-30","Food: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to include, within the recently announced review of VAT, a consideration of the levels of customs and excise duties applied to those drinks and foods which research suggests are most responsible for avoidable deaths and chronic illnesses; and whether they have any plans to introduce a hypothecated tax for the NHS.","false","Biography information for Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe",,"Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe","HL5111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680987","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-13","<p>Historical statistics on residential property transactions and Stamp Duty Land Tax (SDLT) receipts, by financial year, are published in HMRC's 'Annual Stamp Tax Statistics' publication, available on Gov.uk. The latest available data is for the financial year 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>The statistics in the table below are aggregates from the publication and do not include residential properties taxed at the ‘corporate bodies’ rate.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>Property transactions over £1.5 million (thousands)</p></td><td><p>SDLT revenue from these transactions (£ million)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>1,025</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>1,325</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>1,580</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>1,855</p></td></tr></tbody></table>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-02-13T15:27:42.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680987/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680987/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680987/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-30","Housing: Sales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many residential property transactions over £1.5 million there were, and how much Stamp Duty Land Tax revenue those transactions generated, in (1) 2013, (2) 2014, (3) 2015, and (4) 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Macpherson of Earl's Court",,"Lord Macpherson of Earl’s Court","HL5112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680988","Department for Education","false","2017-02-02","<p>All schools have a capacity number written into their funding agreement. Should an academy, including a free school, wish to increase their capacity by 30 places or more, they must apply for approval of a physical expansion of the academy premises. This is set out in the ‘significant changes to an existing academy’ guidance.</p><p> </p><p>If they change their admission arrangements at the same time, they must follow the requirements of the ‘school admissions code’.</p><p> </p><p>Both guidance documents are published on gov.uk copies have been attached.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-02-02T17:07:54.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680988/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680988/answer","School_Admissions_Code_2014_-_19_Dec.pdf ; Making_significant_changes_to_an_open_academy.pdf","School_Admissions_Code_2014_-_19_Dec.pdf ; Making_significant_changes_to_an_open_academy.pdf","School_Admissions_Code_2014 ; Making_significant_changes_to_an_academy","School_Admissions_Code_2014 ; Making_significant_changes_to_an_academy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680988/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Free Schools","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the procedure for increasing the previously agreed size of a particular free school.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680989","Department for Education","false","2017-02-06","<p>Of the 268 mainstream free schools opened up to and including September 2016, 76% have opened in areas where there was a need for additional school places.</p><p>Free schools are approved for a variety of reasons, including the need for new school places, the need for better quality places in the local area, to increase parental choice or to meet demand from local employers. More than a quarter of inspected free schools (reports published by 31<sup>st</sup> December 2016) are rated outstanding by Ofsted. .</p><p>In all cases due consideration is given to the impact that opening a new school will have on local schools.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-02-06T14:28:51.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680989/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680989/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680989/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Schools: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they safeguard against new schools being built in areas of considerable surplus capacity.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680991","Department for Education","false","2017-02-02","<p>We are investing £90m over this Parliament to ensure that every young person has equal access to the life-changing advice and inspiration that they need to fulfil their potential and succeed in life. This includes funding for The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company.</p><p>The Company is continuing to make excellent progress towards transforming the provision of careers, enterprise and employer engagement experiences for young people. Over 1,300 secondary schools and colleges across the country have signed up to the Company’s Enterprise Adviser Network. Of those that have signed up, 1,200 are secondary schools, with 957 matched with an Enterprise Adviser volunteer.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-02-02T15:08:19.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680991/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/680991/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Enterprise Advisers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many schools in England engage with Enterprise Advisers.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL5115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681146","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-02-02","<p>The figures for the total costs associated with the case will be published in due course. <br><br><br><br><br><br></p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-02T16:28:13.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681146/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681146/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681146/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-01-30","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, when he plans to publish the total costs to the public purse of R (on the application of Miller and Dos Santos) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union in the (a) High Court and (b) Supreme Court.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","62196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681147","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>The pay range for directly employed London cleaning staff is £20,188 - £24,430 per annum.</p><p>The rate of pay per hour for cleaning staff employed by our Facilities Management contractors ranges from £6.80 to £9.40 for those aged under 21 and from £7.20 to £9.40 for those aged 21 and over, depending on the contract of the employee.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-07T10:11:50.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681147/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681147/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-30","Cabinet Office: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the hourly pay-rate is for his Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681148","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>The first duty of Government is to safeguard the nation, and we treat cyber security extremely seriously.</p><p>Our system of paper balloting and hand counting means UK voting mechanisms do not lend themselves to direct electronic manipulation.</p><p>The new National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) offers UK organisations, including political parties, access to the best cyber security advice and support to help them meet their responsibility to protect their information and prevent cyber attacks from all possible threats.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-07T10:20:20.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681148/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681148/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-30","Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether any cyber attacks have been carried out on the UK which had the potential to affect its democratic processes.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","62244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681149","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Government is taking a number of ambitious steps to deliver the new National Cyber Security Strategy. This is supported by an increased, transformational investment of £1.9bn across a five year spending period.</p><p> </p><p>A significant recent success was the launch of the National Cyber Security Centre. The Centre is working to deliver the National Cyber Security Strategy, to improve the UK’s ability to respond to major cyber incidents, provide expert guidance on cyber security and push technological innovation for better, more automatic large-scale cyber security.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-03T11:32:24.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681149/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681149/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-30","Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking beyond those outlined in the Cyber Security Strategy of November 2016 to defend the UK from cyber attacks from abroad.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","62245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681150","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Treasury does not currently have plans to publish additional documents for this purpose. ‎The Treasury will notify Parliament of any documents it does bring forward in the normal ways. We continue to make progress in preparing for the UK’s exit from the EU and ensuring we get the best deal for the UK.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-02-07T15:00:18.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681150/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681150/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-30","Treasury: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will place in the Library a list of public consultations, White Papers and other documents his Department plans to publish to assist the UK in making effective the Government's plans for the UK to leave the EU within the two year timetable from the triggering of Article 50.","false","Biography information for Ms Gisela Stuart","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Ms Gisela Stuart","62280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681151","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-07","<p>The cleaning service at HM Treasury is provided through a service contract, let by the landlord for 1 Horse Guards Road (Exchequer Partnership). HM Treasury does not directly employ cleaners.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-02-07T10:18:06.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681151/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681151/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-30","Treasury: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the hourly pay-rate is for his Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681152","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) publishes the estimated cost of the income tax exemption of Interest on National Savings Certificates including index-linked certificates here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/main-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/main-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs</a>. Figures of the population benefitting from this relief are not held.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC publishes the estimated cost of the income tax exemption of junior individual savings account savings, Child Trust Fund account savings, life annuities interest, and life insurance premiums here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/minor-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/minor-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs</a>. Figures of the population benefitting from these reliefs are not held.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of individuals saving into Junior ISAs is published here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/number-of-individual-savings-accounts-isas-amounts-subscribed-to-each-component-and-average-subscription" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/number-of-individual-savings-accounts-isas-amounts-subscribed-to-each-component-and-average-subscription</a></p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of Child Trust Funds saved into in previous years can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/child-trust-fund-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/child-trust-fund-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>The numbers of savers is not the same as the number of individuals benefitting from tax relief, as most of these individuals would not be taxpayers even if they saved into normal (not tax advantaged) accounts due to their age and other allowances.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","62176 ; 62205 ; 62206 ; 62207","2017-02-02T16:47:02.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681152/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681152/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-30","Individual Savings Accounts: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people have received income tax exemption for junior individual savings account savings in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","62208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681153","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) publishes the estimated cost of the income tax exemption of Interest on National Savings Certificates including index-linked certificates here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/main-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/main-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs</a>. Figures of the population benefitting from this relief are not held.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC publishes the estimated cost of the income tax exemption of junior individual savings account savings, Child Trust Fund account savings, life annuities interest, and life insurance premiums here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/minor-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/minor-tax-expenditures-and-structural-reliefs</a>. Figures of the population benefitting from these reliefs are not held.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of individuals saving into Junior ISAs is published here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/number-of-individual-savings-accounts-isas-amounts-subscribed-to-each-component-and-average-subscription" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/number-of-individual-savings-accounts-isas-amounts-subscribed-to-each-component-and-average-subscription</a></p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of Child Trust Funds saved into in previous years can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/child-trust-fund-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/child-trust-fund-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>The numbers of savers is not the same as the number of individuals benefitting from tax relief, as most of these individuals would not be taxpayers even if they saved into normal (not tax advantaged) accounts due to their age and other allowances.</p>","