Defence, what the establishment is of HQ Field Army by (a) rank and (b) responsibility.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","62236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681176","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Ministry of Defence continues to work with the Department for Exiting the EU (DExEU) on understanding the implications of withdrawal from the EU for Defence. This includes work to support the various work streams that DExEU have established to support negotiations and other preparations for leaving the EU.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-02-06T16:51:15.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681176/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681176/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-30","Ministry of Defence: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will place in the Library a list of public consultations, White Papers and other documents his Department plans to publish to assist the UK in making effective the Government's plans for the UK to leave the EU within the two year timetable from the triggering of Article 50.","false","Biography information for Ms Gisela Stuart","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Ms Gisela Stuart","62276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681177","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-02","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 1 March 2016 to the hon. Member for Hornsey and Wood Green (Catherine West) to Question 28601.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-02T16:24:11.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681177/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681177/answer","20160301_28601_WQnA_extract_on_MOD_Cleaning_Services.docx","20160301_28601_WQnA_extract_on_MOD_Cleaning_Services.docx","28601 - WQnA extract on MOD Cleaning Services","28601 - WQnA extract on MOD Cleaning Services","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681177/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-30","Ministry of Defence: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the hourly pay-rate is for his Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681178","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-02","<p>Hightown Barracks Army Reserve Centre in Wrexham is home to the headquarters of 101 Battalion Royal Electrical and Mechanical Engineers. Delivered by 16 regular and Full Time Reservists, 31 reservists and eight civil servants (predominantly officers, warrant officers and senior non-commissioned officers and civilian equivalents), the headquarters provides command and administrative functions for the battalion.</p><p>In addition to the battalion headquarters, also occupying the Hightown Barracks Army Reserve Centre are a Platoon from 3rd Battalion The Royal Welsh (31 Reservists including one officer), a detachment from Wales University Officer Training Corps (two senior non-commissioned officers and 25 officer cadets) and a detachment of Clwyd and Gwynedd Army Cadet Force (four adults and 50 cadets). There are currently no plans to close this centre and the Department has consequently had no contact with developers about its future.</p><p>The Army remains committed to North Wales and in addition to those elements above in Hightown Barracks Army Reserve Centre, there will also be Army Reserve units in Colwyn Bay, Llandudno, Caenarfon, and Queensferry. The Army Cadet Force also has a wide geographic spread across the area.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","62174 ; 62282","2017-02-02T16:25:36.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681178/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681178/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-30","Hightown Barracks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what discussions he or officials of his Department have had with developers on the future of the Hightown Barracks site in Wrexham.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","62281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681179","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-02","<p>Hightown Barracks Army Reserve Centre in Wrexham is home to the headquarters of 101 Battalion Royal Electrical and Mechanical Engineers. Delivered by 16 regular and Full Time Reservists, 31 reservists and eight civil servants (predominantly officers, warrant officers and senior non-commissioned officers and civilian equivalents), the headquarters provides command and administrative functions for the battalion.</p><p>In addition to the battalion headquarters, also occupying the Hightown Barracks Army Reserve Centre are a Platoon from 3rd Battalion The Royal Welsh (31 Reservists including one officer), a detachment from Wales University Officer Training Corps (two senior non-commissioned officers and 25 officer cadets) and a detachment of Clwyd and Gwynedd Army Cadet Force (four adults and 50 cadets). There are currently no plans to close this centre and the Department has consequently had no contact with developers about its future.</p><p>The Army remains committed to North Wales and in addition to those elements above in Hightown Barracks Army Reserve Centre, there will also be Army Reserve units in Colwyn Bay, Llandudno, Caenarfon, and Queensferry. The Army Cadet Force also has a wide geographic spread across the area.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","62174 ; 62281","2017-02-02T16:25:35.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681179/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681179/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-30","Royal Electrical and Mechanical Engineers: North Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of merging 101 Battalion REME with 105 Battalion REME in its relations with the communities in (a) Wrexham and (b) North Wales.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","62282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681180","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-02","<p>Information on the numbers and proportion of Service complaints which met the stipulated target of 24 weeks in calendar years 2014 and 2015 is available in the Annual Reports of, respectively, the Service Complaints Commissioner and the Service Complaints Ombudsman. These publications can be found at the following link:</p><p>http://www.servicecomplaintsombudsman.org.uk/service-complaints-ombudsman/publications-and-reports/annual-reports/</p><p>Information for 2016 is currently being compiled for inclusion in the Service Complaints Ombudsman's Annual Report 2016.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-02-02T16:26:16.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681180/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681180/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-30","Armed Forces: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many and what proportion of in-service complaints were not dealt with in the recommended time for disposal within each of the three armed forces in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","62239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681181","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Defence Academy of the United Kingdom provides two educational courses delivered in Burma to the Burmese Army; both comprehensively address human rights. The Managing Defence in the Wider Security Context and the Strategic Leadership Programme are educational courses that promote governance, transparency and accountability, ethics and international law. The courses have specific modules on international humanitarian law, sexual and gender based violence and child soldiers. The courses emphasise the primacy of democratic political oversight and the rule of international law through the majority of subject areas and thus human rights is addressed more thoroughly than in a single module. The forthcoming Managing Defence in the Wider Security Context programme to be delivered in Burma in the early part of this year includes a session specifically dedicated to human rights. UNHCR, UNICEF and UN Women have all contributed to the programmes delivered in Burma.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2017-02-03T14:45:55.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681181/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681181/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-30","Burma: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 23 January 2017 to Question 60298, what assessment has been made of the utility of introducing a human rights specific programme module to the training provided to the Burmese Army.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","62252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681182","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-21","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) analyses allegations of International Humanitarian Law violations arising from air strikes in Yemen conducted by the Saudi-led Coalition. The MOD has not assessed that the Coalition is deliberately targeting civilians.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-02-21T14:32:02.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681182/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681182/answer","Sevenoaks","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681182/answer/previousversion/34731","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681182/answer/previousversion/34731","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-30","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 5 July 2016 to Question 41410, when his Department last carried out an assessment of (a) whether the Saudi-led coalition in Yemen were targeting civilians and (b) that coalition's level of respect for and compliance with international humanitarian law; and if he will place in the Library copies of documentation used in such assessments.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681183","Department for Education","false","2017-02-07","<p>(a) The Department does not have any data source that separately identifies the number of ‘overseas students’ <em>attending schools in the UK</em> where an overseas student is defined as a student who is not normally resident in the UK but has travelled to the UK to study.</p><p>(b) Data published by the Higher Education Statistics Authority (HESA) shows that in 2015/16, 438,000 international students (from both EU and Non-EU countries) were enrolled in UK Higher Education Institutions. Enrolment data for 2016/17 is currently unavailable.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-07T17:47:58.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681183/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681183/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of overseas students currently studying at UK (a) schools and (b) universities.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681184","Department for Education","false","2017-02-06","<p>This information is available in the statistical first release at</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2016</a></p><p>Figures for England are in table 2c. Figures for each local authority are in tables 7f and 7g.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-06T17:54:56.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681184/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681184/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Faith Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will list the number of faith schools in England by (a) religion and (b) local authority area.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681185","Department for Education","false","2017-02-06","<p>In the 2015 calendar year, 14 new state-funded mainstream schools opened in England. The table below gives a breakdown of this number by local authority.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Local Authority</p></td><td><p>Total faith schools opened in 2015 calendar year</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Birmingham</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Plymouth</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hillingdon</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hounslow</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Norfolk</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Staffordshire</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Kingston upon Thames</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Manchester</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Slough</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lancashire</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Stockton-on-Tees</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Derby</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Buckinghamshire</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>England Total</strong></p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source Edubase</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-06T17:57:34.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681185/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681185/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Faith Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the number of faith schools that were opened in 2015; and where each of those schools are situated.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681186","Department for Education","false","2017-02-07","<p>Cleaning services in buildings managed by the Department are outsourced under a facilities management contract. Suppliers are responsible for setting rates of pay for their staff and rates for cleaners vary dependent on location and market rates. They have informed the Department that they currently pay between £8.25 and £9.40 per hour to staff for cleaning the Department’s buildings.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-07T11:47:54.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681186/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681186/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Department for Education: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the hourly pay-rate is for her Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681187","Department for Education","false","2017-02-08","<p>Through our careful management of the economy we have been able to protect the core schools budget in real terms. That means schools are receiving more funding than ever before for children’s education, totalling over £40 billion this year.</p><p>When the Government launched our <em>Educational Excellence Everywhere </em>White Paper, it was clear that we would listen and reflect on the discussions. After listening to the sector, in May 2016 the Department confirmed that it would no longer be pursuing full academisation by 2022. Removing the absolute time pressure changes the scale of financial support we need to make available over the remainder of this Parliament</p><p>It remains the Government’s ambition that the whole school system ultimately benefits from the autonomy and freedom to innovate that academy status brings, and that schools work together in collaboration through strong multi-academy trusts. The Department still has sufficient funding – voted during the Spending Review – to ensure schools can take advantage of the opportunities available by becoming an academy. This includes funding to support schools to convert and to build capacity in the system, including recruiting excellent sponsors and encouraging the development of strong multi-academy trusts.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-08T13:52:19.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681187/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681187/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Academies: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reason her Department plans to return budgetary provision allocated to supporting the costs of academisation to HM Treasury.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","62224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681188","Department for Education","false","2017-02-16","<p>The number of places initially allocated for citizenship each year since the academic year 2013/14 is shown in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Academic year (of training)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Initial allocation of citizenship places</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>147</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>149</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>175</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Published ITT Allocations Official Statistics.[1]</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Data for earlier years are not directly comparable with those shown in the table as they include allocations for Personal, Social and Health Education and Social Studies within the total for Citizenship.</p><p> </p><p>[1] This includes postgraduate and undergraduate allocated places.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-16T15:02:00.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681188/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681188/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Citizenship: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many places were available for trainee teachers who wish to specialise in citizenship education on teacher training courses in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","62229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681189","Department for Education","false","2017-02-16","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that high quality citizenship education helps to provide pupils with knowledge, skills and understanding to prepare them to play a full and active part in society.</p><p>Citizenship education is therefore part of the National Curriculum at Key Stages 3 and 4. The revised programmes of study were introduced in September 2014 and seek to direct teaching towards the core knowledge of citizenship, and to give schools more scope to decide how to teach citizenship.</p><p>The Secretary of State is considering the proposal in the White Paper regarding citizenship.</p><p>Teachers are encouraged to develop their practice with the support of specialist organisations and expert professionals such as subject associations.</p><p> </p><p>Ofsted, in its inspections of schools, considers the breadth and balance of the curriculum, including provision for pupils’ personal development, behaviour and welfare, as well as their spiritual, moral, social and cultural development. This includes how pupils develop and demonstrate skills and attitudes that will allow them to participate fully in and contribute positively to life in modern Britain. Ofsted have strengthened their inspection frameworks so that inspectors assess how well all schools protect pupils from the risks of extremism and radicalisation, and promote fundamental British values.</p><p> </p><p>We are also supporting schools to meet their obligations to protect pupils from radicalisation and promote fundamental British values, and to help them build pupils’ resilience to extremism through knowledge so that they can question information, weigh arguments, and make reasoned judgments.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently working with the Association of Citizenship Teaching on producing guidance and resources packs to help teachers lead knowledge based debates on topics relating to extremism, fundamental British values and contemporary political and social issues.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","62346","2017-02-16T14:58:32.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681189/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681189/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Citizenship: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to ensure effective teaching of citizenship education in schools in England; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","62230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681190","Department for Education","false","2017-02-02","<p>We have not provided any funding specifically for deaf awareness training. However, over the past six years, we have provided £2.25million of funding to a partnership of sensory impairment charities through the National Sensory Impairment Partnership (NatSIP), to improve outcomes for children and young people with sensory impairment. Through NatSIP, we have worked with charities such as the National Deaf Children’s Society to produce resources such as the 'Supporting the achievement of deaf children' pack, a comprehensive set of guides on how teachers can support children and young people with hearing impairment. In addition, as set out in the Equality Act 2010, we expect all schools to support disabled children and young people, including by making reasonable adjustments to prevent them from suffering discrimination.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-02-02T09:54:01.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681190/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681190/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-30","Schools: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding her Department provided for support for deaf awareness training in schools in (a) St Helens North constituency, (b) the North West and (c) England in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","62190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681191","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-02","<p>According to the latest HMRC trade data, the provisional value of UK exports of food &amp; drink to the EU for the 12 month period December 2015 to November 2016 was £11.8 billion.</p><p> </p><p>Approximately 50% (£5.9 billion) of these exports were raw or lightly-processed goods related to the agricultural sector. The remaining 50% of exports were highly-processed goods related to the food &amp; drink manufacturing sector.</p><p> </p><p>Agricultural trade data is not available for the geographic detail requested in parts (a) and (b).</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-02T10:43:51.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681191/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681191/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-30","Agriculture: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the economic value of agricultural exports to the EU in (a) St Helens North constituency, (b) the North West and (c) the UK in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","62187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681192","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-07","<p>The commercial data was extracted from the Trade Control and Expert System (TRACES) and the pet data was taken from APHA’s system for recording pets entering the UK, based on information provided by pet checkers.</p><p> </p><p>In some cases imports are recorded on TRACES as “Canis familiaris / Felis catus”, so APHA are unable to distinguish between cat or dog imports. These are included on the table in row “Mixed cats/dogs”.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Pets</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Commercial</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dogs</p></td><td><p>275,876</p></td><td><p>34,017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cats</p></td><td><p>24,145</p></td><td><p>2,572</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ferrets</p></td><td><p>129</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mixed cats/dogs</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td><td><p>327</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-07T15:06:50.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681192/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681192/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-30","Pets: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many (a) dogs, (b) cats and (c) ferrets were imported (i) non-commercially under the Pets Travel Scheme and (ii) commercially under the Trade in Animals and Related Products Regulations 2011 into the UK in 2016.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","62238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681193","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-09","<p>Defra’s office cleaners are provided through a facilities management contract and are paid the following hourly rates as a minimum:-</p><ul><li><p>Outside of London boroughs £8.25 rising to £8.45 from April 2017</p></li><li><p>Within London boroughs - £9.40 rising to £9.75 from April 2017</p></li></ul><p>.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-09T10:46:30.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681193/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681193/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-30","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the hourly pay-rate is for her Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681194","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-07","<p>Defra is planning to publish two Green Papers, one on our 25 year plan for the environment, and one on our 25 year plan for food, farming and fisheries. The Department is considering options for legislative and non-legislative measures to achieve a smooth and orderly exit from the EU, including through the Great Repeal Bill. We will confirm plans in due course.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-07T11:40:32.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681194/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681194/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-30","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will place in the Library a list of public consultations, White Papers and other documents her Department plans to publish to assist the UK in making effective the Government's plans for the UK to leave the EU within the two year timetable from the triggering of Article 50.","false","Biography information for Ms Gisela Stuart","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Ms Gisela Stuart","62277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681195","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>Cleaning services to the Foreign and Commonwealth Office's UK Estate, are provided by Interserve, as part of a facilities management contract. Interserve are responsible for setting rates of pay for their staff and have informed the FCO that they currently pay £7.20 per hour to staff for cleaning the FCO's UK buildings. This will rise to £7.50 per hour on 1 April 2017.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-07T15:41:54.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681195/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681195/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the hourly pay-rate is for his Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681196","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>The UK Government does not shy away from raising legitimate human rights concerns. We regularly raise the death penalty with the Saudi authorities, most recently on 19 January.</p><p>The UK Government opposes the death penalty in all circumstances and in every country, including Saudi Arabia, especially for crimes other than the most serious and for juveniles, in line Article Six of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights and the Arab Charter on Human Rights.</p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-07T14:07:59.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681196/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681196/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Saudi Arabia: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 16 June 2016 to Questions 40437 and 40433, when his Department last made representations to Saudi Arabia (a) expressing concern about the extent of the application of and (b) encouraging abolition of the death penalty in that country.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681197","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>In line with our obligations under the Convention on Cluster Munitions, we regularly encourage Saudi Arabia, as a non-party to the Convention, to accede to it. The most recent Ministerial engagement on this issue was in October. Foreign Office Ministers, our Ambassador to Saudi Arabia and officials have frequent meetings with the Saudi government and officials to discuss a full range of regional and bilateral issues.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-07T14:15:12.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681197/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681197/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Saudi Arabia: Convention on Cluster Munitions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 16 June 2016 to Question 40456, what recent representations the UK has made to Saudi Arabia to accede to the Convention on Cluster Munitions; and on what dates those representations were made.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681198","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>We remain deeply concerned by the ongoing detention of Dr Mudawi Ibrahim Adam, and allegations that he has been tortured. Both our Ambassador in Khartoum and the UK Special Representative for Sudan and South Sudan most recently raised our concerns about this case directly with senior Sudanese Government figures, including Foreign Minister Ibrahim Ghandour on 24 January, during the visit of the UK Special Representative to Khartoum between 21-28 January. Officials from our Embassy in Khartoum also pressed the Sudanese government to allow access for Dr Mudawi’s family, and we are aware that they visited him in prison on 27 January.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-02T16:36:21.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681198/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681198/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Mudawi Ibrahim Adam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the UK Special Representative for Sudan and South Sudan, Chris Trott, raised the ongoing detention without charge of Dr Mudawi Ibrahim Adam during his meeting with the Sudanese Foreign Minister, Ibrahim Ghandour, on 24 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","62226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681199","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>We remain deeply concerned by the ongoing detention of Dr Mudawi Ibrahim Adam, and allegations that he has been tortured. Both our Ambassador in Khartoum and the UK Special Representative for Sudan and South Sudan most recently raised our concerns about this case directly with senior Sudanese government figures, including Foreign Minister Ibrahim Ghandour on 24 January, during the visit of the UK Special Representative to Khartoum between 21-28 January. Officials from our Embassy in Khartoum also pressed the Sudanese government to allow access for Dr Mudawi’s family, and we are aware that they visited him in prison on 27 January.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-02T16:38:40.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681199/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681199/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Mudawi Ibrahim Adam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received on the alleged torture of Dr Mudawi Ibrahim Adam by Sudanese authorities during his ongoing detention without charge; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","62227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681200","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>All parts of government are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK. This means having talented people with the right skills in the right places. We are not in a position to give final details on future staff numbers in UKREP or elsewhere in government as this work is continuing.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-02-02T16:54:42.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681200/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681200/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","UK Permanent Representation to the EU: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to increase the size of the UK Representation to the EU once negotiations begin on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681201","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-07","<p>This Government believes that a fair and effective criminal justice system is an essential underpinning for states seeking to respect human rights and to prosper. The UK has useful experience to offer other states. Our criminal justice advisers play a valuable role in sharing this experience to the mutual benefit of the UK and the international community.</p><p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has not conducted any formal assessment of the work of HMG country criminal justice advisers. These advisers, most of whom are employed by the Crown Prosecution Service, are based across a number of posts around the world.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-07T15:46:26.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681201/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681201/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-30","Criminal Proceedings: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how his Department assesses the work of country criminal justice advisors; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","62144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681202","Department of Health","false","2017-02-07","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence has the necessary capacity to develop technology appraisal guidance on all the technologies prioritised through its established topic selection processes, including drugs and treatments for muscle-wasting conditions and other rare diseases.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-07T15:54:00.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681202/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681202/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to increase the capacity of NICE's appraisal processes for (a) muscle-wasting treatments and (b) treatments for other rare diseases.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","62147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681203","Department of Health","false","2017-02-07","<p>Patients and their families affected by rare diseases and muscle-wasting conditions often require emotional and psychological support. NHS England has committed to a number of national priorities to improve the support available including the Improved Access to Psychological Therapies programme and the Government’s choice commitment to end of life care. Teams within NHS England’s medical directorate are working with a wide range of stakeholders and patient representatives to embed person-centred care for all patients with long-term life limiting conditions.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-07T10:06:53.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681203/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681203/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to improve access to emotional and psychological support for people with (a) muscle-wasting conditions and (b) other rare diseases.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","62148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681204","Department of Health","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Information Sharing to Tackle Violence (ISTV) programme is a Department of Health-funded cross-government programme informed by the Cardiff Model and designed to reduce knife, gun and all other violent forms of crime. It is a key deliverable for the Government in addressing crime.</p><p> </p><p>Collecting data on serious violent incidents is a requirement on Type 1 accident and emergency (A&amp;E) services. Non-confidential ISTV data is shared with local Community Safety Partnership (CSP) colleagues for use as a basis for crime prevention strategies. High quality information from hospitals can be used by CSPs to tackle all forms of violence through local interventions such as targeted policing or applying licensing restrictions to bars and clubs. The Department published “<em>Information Sharing to Tackle Violence Guidance for Community Safety Partnerships on engaging with the NHS</em>” (2012) which included practical tools and guidance for CSP partners.</p><p> </p><p>The Department secured funding for the Violence Reduction Nurse project which aims to implement the ISTV data standard consistently across hospitals in England. Since 2015 this has covered the costs of 12 Violence Reduction Nurses who alongside their other duties work to set up systems within their own A&amp;E and to support up to 20 more hospitals in their region to adopt the information standard. Public Health England is supporting the standardisation of data collection, including injury data, in Emergency Departments through the Emergency Care Data Set.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-07T17:46:06.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681204/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681204/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Accident and Emergency Departments: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps (a) he and (b) his Department are taking to promote and implement the accident and emergency-based Cardiff model for violence prevention in England.","false","Biography information for Craig Williams","Cardiff North","Craig Williams","62157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681205","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>Hidradenitis suppurativa (HS) can usually be managed through routine access to primary or secondary care. For those patients with the most serious forms of HS, who cannot be managed in this way, a referral to an appropriate specialised service may be appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>The list of specialised dermatology providers for both in-patient and out-patient care is attached.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England commissions specialised services for people with rare and complex skin conditions and has set out what providers must have in place in order to offer specialist dermatology care. The level of service provision nationally is based on an assessment of the likely patient population who will need to access specialised care. It is estimated that about 10% of patients requiring dermatology services (about 10,000 each year) need care from specialised dermatology centres.</p><p> </p><p>More information on the service specification for specialised dermatology can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/a12-spec-dermatology.pdf" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/a12-spec-dermatology.pdf</a></p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","62255","2017-02-02T16:27:10.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681205/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681205/answer","PQ62194 attached document.XLSX","PQ62194 attached document.XLSX","PQ62194 attached document","PQ62194 attached document","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681205/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Hidradenitis Suppurativa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will place in the Library a list of designated centres for the treatment of hidradenitis suppurativa that is difficult to diagnose or manage.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","62194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681206","Department of Health","false","2017-02-07","<p>NHS England set aside £25 million to fund new treatments approved as part of the annual prioritisation process for specialised services process for 2016-17.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-07T10:07:57.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681206/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681206/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what funds were available to NHS England to finance the annual prioritisation process for specialised services in 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","62199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681207","Department of Health","false","2017-02-07","<p>NHS England has provisionally set aside £25 million to fund new treatments and interventions being considered as part of the 2017/18 annual prioritisation process.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-07T10:08:57.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681207/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681207/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what funds NHS England will provide for the annual prioritisation process for specialised services in 2017.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","62200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681208","Department of Health","false","2017-02-07","<p>The exact number of policy proposals going forward to the annual specialised commissioning prioritisation process in spring 2017/18 is yet to be finalised.</p><p> </p><p>However, it will include the three policy proposals that were not prioritised on grounds of affordability in the 2016/17 prioritisation round.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-07T10:10:03.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681208/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681208/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many policies are being considered by NHS England's Commissioning department for the annual prioritisation process for specialised services.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","62201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681209","Department of Health","false","2017-02-07","<p>NHS England has a statutory duty to carry out an annual performance assessment of each clinical commissioning group (CCG) and, in 2016/17, introduced the CCG Improvement and Assessment Framework. This framework is aligned to delivery of the Five Year Forward View and NHS Planning Guidance.</p><p> </p><p>The Framework brings together in one place NHS Constitution and other core performance and finance indicators, outcome goals and transformational challenges. CCGs are also assessed against a range of indicators that consider their delivery of commitments, improved health outcomes for their populations and whether they are well-led organisations. This provides assurance that CCGs are effective commissioning organisations.</p><p> </p><p>Where necessary, NHS England is supported by legislation in exercising formal powers of direction if it is satisfied that a CCG is failing or is at risk of failing to discharge its functions.</p><p> </p><p>It is a matter for CCGs to determine how best to commission services to meet the health needs of their local population, and they should have regard to National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance in doing so.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-07T15:50:30.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681209/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681209/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what mechanisms NHS England has in place to ensure that clinical commissioning groups are fulfilling their statutory responsibility to commission certain health services to meet the reasonable requirements of the persons for whom it has responsibility in (a) the prescribing of medical nutrition according to NICE Clinical Guidance 32 2006 and (b) commissioning other health services in line with section 13(2) of the Health and Social Care Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Maggie Throup","Erewash","Maggie Throup","62211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681210","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STPs) are locally led plans designed to reflect the priorities and needs of the area. As such it is for individual STPs, which we expect to be developed in partnership with local authorities, to determine the impact on social care costs. Through better integration of health and social care across an area we believe can improve patient experience.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-02T16:31:37.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681210/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681210/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","NHS: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the implementation of sustainability and transformation plans on social care costs for local authorities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","62225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681211","Department of Health","false","2017-02-06","<p>NHS England introduced its annual relative prioritisation process for specialised services in 2016, following a period of public consultation. As this process did not exist in 2015, no funds were set aside for it during that year.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-06T13:41:13.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681211/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681211/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what funds were available to NHS England to finance the annual prioritisation process for specialised services in 2015.","false","Biography information for Andrea Jenkyns","Morley and Outwood","Andrea Jenkyns","62198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681212","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>Exit checks were introduced in April 2015 and will, over a period of time, provide us with this information. My Department is considering the use of exit checks data for statistical reporting purposes. A report on statistics being collected under the exit checks programme was published on 25 August 2016 and is available on the UK Government website www.gov.uk. Any data published will be subject to data assurance standards.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-02T16:35:18.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681212/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681212/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have been recorded as having left the UK by border exit checks in 2015 and 2016 since their introduction in April 2015.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681213","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>Hidradenitis suppurativa (HS) can usually be managed through routine access to primary or secondary care. For those patients with the most serious forms of HS, who cannot be managed in this way, a referral to an appropriate specialised service may be appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>The list of specialised dermatology providers for both in-patient and out-patient care is attached.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England commissions specialised services for people with rare and complex skin conditions and has set out what providers must have in place in order to offer specialist dermatology care. The level of service provision nationally is based on an assessment of the likely patient population who will need to access specialised care. It is estimated that about 10% of patients requiring dermatology services (about 10,000 each year) need care from specialised dermatology centres.</p><p> </p><p>More information on the service specification for specialised dermatology can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="http://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/a12-spec-dermatology.pdf" target="_blank">www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/a12-spec-dermatology.pdf</a></p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","62194","2017-02-02T16:27:10.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681213/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681213/answer","PQ62194 attached document.XLSX","PQ62194 attached document.XLSX","PQ62194 attached document","PQ62194 attached document","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681213/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Hidradenitis Suppurativa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to NHS England's service specification for specialised dermatology services, if he will place in the Library a list of designated centres for the treatment of hidradenitis suppurativa that is difficult to diagnose or manage.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","62255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681214","Department of Health","false","2017-02-07","<p>The following table shows the estimated cost of tooth extractions for patients aged 18 years and under from 2010/11 to 2015/16. The data covers all tooth extractions/removals, and does not distinguish between deciduous or adult teeth.</p><p> </p><p>The data source for the table is from reference costs, which are the average unit costs to National Health Service trusts and NHS foundation trusts of providing defined services in a given financial year to NHS patients. Reference costs for acute care are collected by healthcare resource group, which are standard groupings of clinically similar treatments which use common levels of healthcare resource.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="6"><p>Estimated total cost £ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Health Resource Group Description</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Major Surgical Removal of Tooth, 18 years and under</p></td><td><p>4.3</p></td><td><p>5.3</p></td><td><p>5.7</p></td><td><p>6.3</p></td><td><p>6.7</p></td><td><p>6.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Surgical Removal of Tooth, 18 years and under</p></td><td><p>10.6</p></td><td><p>11.0</p></td><td><p>9.7</p></td><td><p>9.9</p></td><td><p>10.7</p></td><td><p>10.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Extraction of Multiple Teeth, 18 years and under</p></td><td><p>21.9</p></td><td><p>23.7</p></td><td><p>27.4</p></td><td><p>31.4</p></td><td><p>35.4</p></td><td><p>35.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Minor Extraction of Tooth, 18 years and under</p></td><td><p>2.7</p></td><td><p>2.9</p></td><td><p>3.1</p></td><td><p>2.9</p></td><td><p>3.1</p></td><td><p>3.3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Department of Health, Reference Costs</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-07T15:43:49.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681214/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681214/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Dental Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much has been spent on child tooth extraction in hospitals in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","62250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681215","Department of Health","false","2017-02-07","<p>The hourly pay-rate for the Department’s cleaners is £8.45.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-07T10:05:37.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681215/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681215/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-30","Department of Health: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the hourly pay-rate is for his Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681216","Home Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>Cleaning services across the department are outsourced. Suppliers are responsible for setting rates of pay for their staff and rates for cleaners vary dependent on their age, location and market rates. They have informed the department that they currently pay, as a minimum, either the National Minimum Wage or the National Living Wage for cleaning the department’s buildings.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-06T14:15:02.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681216/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681216/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Home Office: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the hourly pay-rate is for her Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681217","Home Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Government has always been committed to parliamentary scrutiny of our withdrawal from the EU, balanced against the need to avoid undermining our negotiating position, as agreed by the House of Commons on 12 October 2016. The Government will put the final deal that is agreed between the UK and the EU to a vote in both Houses of Parliament, before it comes into force.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-06T13:57:37.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681217/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681217/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Home Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will place in the Library a list of public consultations, White Papers and other documents her Department plans to publish to assist the UK in making effective the Government's plans for the UK to leave the EU within the two year timetable from the triggering of Article 50.","false","Biography information for Ms Gisela Stuart","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Ms Gisela Stuart","62278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681218","Home Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>This information is not held centrally within the Home Office. The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-06T13:56:40.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681218/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681218/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Home Office: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many civil servants have been seconded from her Department to the Department for Exiting the European Union.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681219","Home Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Government seeks to ensure the availability of funding and resources to deliver against its commitments.</p><p>At the height of the operation in Calais the UK had deployed over 200 Home Office staff, interpreters and social workers who visited the specialist centres in France to carry out the necessary assessments to determine whether it was in the best interests of the children to be transferred to the UK. We have also seconded an expert to Greece in addition to our long-standing secondee in Italy to support efforts to identify children who may qualify for transfer to the UK under section 67 of the Immigration Act and the Dublin Regulation.</p><p>The Home Office pays a national rate of £114 per day (£41,610 pa) for every UASC under the age of 16 and £91 per day for every UASC age 16 or 17 (£33,215 pa). These rates represent a 20% and 28% increase respectively on the previous rates. We also pay £200 per week (£10,400 pa) as a contribution towards leaving care costs for former UASC aged 18 and over who have leave to remain in the UK, this represents a 33% increase on the previous rate.</p><p>More broadly, the Government has established a £10 million Refugee Children Fund for Europe to support the needs of vulnerable refugee and migrant children arriving in Europe.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-06T13:47:32.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681219/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681219/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what (a) financial and (b) other resources have been allocated to support the implementation of section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","62237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681220","Home Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The information requested is not held centrally by the Home Office.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office collects and publishes data on the number of arrests by each police force in England and Wales at offence group level (e.g. violence against the person, sexual offences etc.). However, the data cannot be broken down to specifically identify the number of arrests for controlling or coercive behaviour in an intimate or family relationship (coercive control).</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to improving the data on domestic abuse. The Office for National Statistics has published a new statistical bulletin that brings together comprehensive data on domestic abuse at a local level. Additional data will be added to the annual series as it becomes available.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for professionals on the new offence of coercive control was published in December 2015 and the Crown Prosecution Service is closely monitoring performance. New transformative training has been piloted by the College of Policing and is in the process of being rolled out further.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","62233","2017-02-06T10:54:50.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681220/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681220/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Domestic Abuse: Arrests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many arrests have been made for the offence of coercive control in each region and constituent part of the UK in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","62234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681221","Home Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The information requested is not held centrally by the Home Office.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office collects and publishes data on the number of arrests by each police force in England and Wales at offence group level (e.g. violence against the person, sexual offences etc.). However, the data cannot be broken down to specifically identify the number of arrests for controlling or coercive behaviour in an intimate or family relationship (coercive control).</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to improving the data on domestic abuse. The Office for National Statistics has published a new statistical bulletin that brings together comprehensive data on domestic abuse at a local level. Additional data will be added to the annual series as it becomes available.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for professionals on the new offence of coercive control was published in December 2015 and the Crown Prosecution Service is closely monitoring performance. New transformative training has been piloted by the College of Policing and is in the process of being rolled out further.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","62234","2017-02-06T10:54:50.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681221/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681221/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much time each police force in England has allocated to train officers on the offence of coercive control.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","62233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681222","Home Office","true","2017-02-02","<p>We have not received a proposal from the Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner regarding the establishment of a central repository for modern slavery statements. We have not endorsed a particular repository for such statements. So far, two repository websites have been set up to collect the ‘slavery and human trafficking statements’ published by businesses in one place<del class="ministerial">. These are being run by Unseen and the Business and Human Rights Resource Centre</del>.<ins class="ministerial"> These are being run by Semantrica and the Business and Human Rights Resource Centre.</ins></p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-02T16:41:43.46Z","2017-02-21T14:16:34.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681222/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681222/answer","Truro and Falmouth","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681222/answer/previousversion/33834","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681222/answer/previousversion/33834","Biography information for Sarah Newton","1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of proposals by the Anti-Slavery Commissioners to establish a central repository for modern slavery statements; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","62209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681223","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Secretary of State for the Home Department has appointed the new Chair of the Migration Advisory Committee, the Chair of the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs, and two Non-Executive Board members for the Disclosure and Barring Service.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-02T16:43:02.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681223/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681223/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Home Office: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what public appointments she has made since her appointment.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681224","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Home Secretary last visited the College of Policing on 30 November 2016 for its annual conference, held at Sunningdale. The Home Secretary presented a key note speech.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-02-02T16:39:49.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681224/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681224/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","College of Policing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she last visited the College of Policing.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681225","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government takes this issue seriously, which is why we commissioned private advice from the Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner. His advice has informed the significant work we have undertaken over recent months. This includes offering over 70 experts to support the hotspot response, funding psycho-social support to refugees and migrants on the Greek islands, funding training, accommodation and a scaled-up counter-trafficking response in Italy, and funding more effective case management support in Greece.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-02T16:43:49.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681225/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681225/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-30","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to publish the report received from Kevin Hyland following his visit to hotspots in Greece and Italy in 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","62156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681226","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-06","<p>The full implications of the reinstated and expanded Mexico City policy are not yet clear, but we are closely following developments. DFID will consider the implications with our offices, with UK civil society and with donors.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-06T17:38:27.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681226/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681226/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","USA: Family Planning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effect of the US restoring the Mexico City Policy on the effectiveness of her Department's projects.","false","Biography information for Mike Freer","Finchley and Golders Green","Mike Freer","62149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681227","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Secretary of State announced to the International Development Committee (IDC) on 19 December that DFID will conduct a fundamental review of supplier practices which will include looking at how to drive greater transparency of costs in our supply chain.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-02T17:48:44.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681227/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681227/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Department for International Development: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans she has to cap the daily rate of consultants working (a) directly for and (b) for contractors working on projects funded by her Department.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","62150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681228","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-02","<p>The availability of some medical supplies and services in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs) can be restricted by Israeli security procedures. A recent World Health Organisation (WHO) report noted increasing restrictions, notably permit delays or denial, for patients who have been referred for further care outside Gaza and the West Bank. For Gaza this is particularly acute, and is compounded by frequent closure by Egypt of the Rafah crossing, preventing urgent medical cases from seeking treatment in Egypt.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-02T17:44:49.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681228/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681228/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Gaza and West Bank: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effect of Israel's border restrictions and permit system on urgent medical care for people resident in (a) the West Bank and (b) Gaza.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","62175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681229","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-02","<p>Over the last five years, the UK Government has provided £3.87 billion for climate action in developing countries. This has, amongst other things, supported 21 million people to cope with the effects of climate change and helped 6.6 million people access clean energy.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-02T17:49:17.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681229/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681229/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Developing Countries: Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much government funding is provided for climate action in developing countries.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","62257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681230","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-06","<p>We welcome the educational targets of UNESCO's Policy Paper. Well trained, motivated and empowered teachers are central to a quality education and this is where we are focusing our efforts; in the period 2011 – 2015 we helped to train 380,000 teachers and improve the effectiveness of teacher development. Through our ongoing bilateral education programmes and support to the Global Partnership for Education (GPE), we assist 65 developing countries to develop and finance education sector plans for teacher training.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-06T17:12:55.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681230/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681230/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Developing Countries: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the implications are for her policies on her Department's assistance for the training of teachers in the developing world to meet 2030 educational targets of UNESCOs Policy Paper 19 of April 2015, The challenge of teacher shortage and quality.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","62246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681231","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-06","<p>Yes, but currently none have been published.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-06T17:13:55.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681231/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681231/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will place in the Library a list of public consultations, White Papers and other documents her Department plans to publish to assist the UK in making effective the Government's plans for the UK to leave the EU within the two year timetable from the triggering of Article 50.","false","Biography information for Ms Gisela Stuart","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Ms Gisela Stuart","62279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681232","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-06","<p>DFID utilises a cross government contract for cleaning services in their UK estates. Cleaners are currently paid an hourly rate of £9.40 in DFID’s London office and £8.25 in DFID’s East Kilbride office.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-06T17:19:07.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681232/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681232/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-30","Department for International Development: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the hourly pay-rate is for her Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681233","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-03","<p>In 2015 and 2016 prisoner transfer arrangements were negotiated with Iraq, Ghana, and Taiwan. The Agreements with Iraq and with Ghana are subject to ratification and are not yet in force.</p><p> </p><p>The absence of a prisoner transfer agreement does not prevent the removal of an individual. Those who have no right to remain here will be deported and removed from the UK. Where possible, the UK will seek to remove Foreign National Offenders held in custody through the Early Removal Scheme or seek their deportation at the completion of the prison sentence.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to increasing the number of Foreign National Offenders removed from our prisons, whether they are removed through Prisoner Transfer Agreement or the Early Removal Scheme. Last year we removed the highest number of offenders since records began with a total of 5,810 offenders removed from prisons, immigration removal centres and the community.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-02-03T14:08:41.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681233/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681233/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Prisoners: Repatriation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoner transfer agreements were negotiated in 2015 and 2016; and with which countries those agreements were made.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681234","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-06","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-06T17:42:56.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681234/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681234/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Domestic Abuse: Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications for legal aid in cases involving coercive control have been approved by the Legal Aid Authority in the last 12 months; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","62232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681235","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-07","<p>The information requested in not held centrally.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-07T12:56:22.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681235/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681235/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average length of time was for a case to be determined from the time appeal papers arrive at the First Tier Tribunal office to determination of that appeal in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681236","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-07","<p>The government takes animal welfare very seriously and continues to keep the maximum penalties under review.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-07T13:08:16.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681236/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681236/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Animal Welfare: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will commence section 281(5) of the Criminal Justice Act 2003 to allow for penalties available under section 32 of the Animal Welfare Act 2006 to come into force.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","62231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681237","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-02","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service has commissioned a design for replacement custody facilities at Wrexham Magistrates’ Court. This will be evaluated as part of the assessment of options for the future provision of custodial facilities at Wrexham Magistrates Court. The evaluation will take place in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-02T13:29:45.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681237/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681237/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Magistrates' Courts: Wrexham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans her Department has for the construction of custody facilities at Wrexham Magistrates' Court; what options for that construction her Department is assessing; and what the timetable is for her Department to make decisions on the (a) options and (b) construction of such facilities.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","62218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681238","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-15","<p>The Secretary of State for Justice has visited HM Courts &amp; Tribunal Service operational venues in Central London, Norwich, Maidstone and Bristol. She plans to continue her programme of visits over the coming months.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-15T13:51:26.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681238/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681238/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-30","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when she last observed proceedings at a First-tier Immigration Tribunal.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681239","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Office for National Statistics publish annually the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organisation as part of the Civil Service Statistics and this information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</a></p><p> </p><p>The Northern Ireland Office sponsors a number of arms-length bodies located in Northern Ireland, which are aligned to the pay and grading arrangements for the Northern Ireland Civil Service. As these bodies are independent of Government, the hon Member may wish to write to them directly on these matters – contact details are set out below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>ALB</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Contact Details</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parades Commission for Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p><a href="mailto:info@paradescommission.org" target="_blank">info@paradescommission.org</a></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission</p></td><td><p><a href="mailto:information@nihrc.org" target="_blank">information@nihrc.org</a></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p><a href="mailto:contact@boundarycommission.org.uk" target="_blank">contact@boundarycommission.org.uk</a></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Office of the Civil Service Commissioners for Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p><a href="mailto:info@nicscommissioners.org" target="_blank">info@nicscommissioners.org</a></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Chief Electoral Officer for Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p><a href="mailto:info@eoni.org.uk" target="_blank">info@eoni.org.uk</a></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-02-02T17:43:18.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681239/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681239/answer",,,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-30","Northern Ireland Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the level of earnings is of the (a) highest and (b) lowest-paid employees of his Department, its agencies and arms-length bodies; and what the median level of earnings is for such employees.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681240","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The responsibility for policing and justice matters in Northern Ireland has been devolved to the Northern Ireland Executive since April 2010. All decisions on prosecutions are taken independently of Government and in accordance with the Code for Prosecutors. While the Northern Ireland Office does not have a full record of prosecutions, I am aware that since November 2015 prosecutions have been brought against three former members of the armed forces for Troubles-related offences. In addition to previous or current prosecutions there are a number of coronial inquests examining cases involving members of the armed forces, while all deaths caused by members of the armed forces are being re-examined by the Legacy Investigations Branch of the PSNI.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-02-02T17:38:43.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681240/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681240/answer",,,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-30","Armed Forces: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many former or serving members of the armed forces have been prosecuted for Troubles-related offences in each year since 1998.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","62188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681241","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-07","<p>I held a bilateral meeting with President Putin in the margins of the G20 Summit in September. Discussions covered Syria and our bilateral relationship.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-02-07T16:54:00.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681241/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681241/answer",,,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-30","Russia: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, when she last held discussions with President Putin.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681242","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-07","<p>I met the Secretary General of the Commonwealth at the UN General Assembly in September 2016. The Minister for the Commonwealth, The Rt Hon. Baroness Anelay of St Johns DBE, meets regularly with the Secretary General, and did so most recently on 21 December 2016.</p><p> </p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-02-07T16:52:41.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681242/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681242/answer",,,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-30","Commonwealth Secretariat","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, when she last met the Secretary General of the Commonwealth.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681243","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-07","<p>I have not yet held discussions with the President of Yemen though the UK engages regularly with President Hadi. Most recently, Minister Ellwood called President Hadi on 15 January.</p><p>The UK government continues to stress to all parties that a political solution is the best way to bring long-term stability to Yemen and end the conflict.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-02-07T16:53:28.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681243/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681243/answer",,,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-30","Yemen: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, when she last held discussions with President Hadi of Yemen.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681244","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-07","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Hornsey and Wood Green (Mrs West) on 31 January 2017, UIN 50210.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","62360 ; 62361","2017-02-07T16:08:25.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681244/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681244/answer",,,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-30","USA: Torture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether she raised the use of torture as an interrogation technique by US intelligence services at her meeting with President Trump on 27 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681245","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-07","<p>A list of special advisers was published on 21st December 2016, and copies have been placed in the libraries of both Houses. Information on the gender and ethnicity of special advisers is not routinely collected.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-02-07T16:54:36.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681245/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681245/answer",,,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-30","Prime Minister: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what the total number of special advisers working at Number 10 is, by (a) gender and (b) ethnic minority background.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","62292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681246","Public Accounts Commission","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Public Accounts Commission does not have any employees. It is a statutory body with a membership of nine Members of the House of Commons. Its role is defined by the National Audit Act 1983 and the Budget Responsibility and National Audit Act 2011. Its principal duties under the Acts are to examine the National Audit Office Estimate and lay it before the House, to consider reports from the appointed auditor of the National Audit Office (NAO), to appoint non-executive members of the NAO Board, and to report from time to time.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Gainsborough","Sir Edward Leigh",,"2017-02-06T10:34:57.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681246/answer","Biography information for Sir Edward Leigh","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681246/answer",,,,,,,,,"24","Public Accounts Commission","Public Accounts Commission","2017-01-30","Public Accounts Commission: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chairman of the Public Accounts Commission, what the level of earnings is of the (a) highest and (b) lowest-paid employees of the Commission; and what the median level of earnings is for such employees.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681247","Scotland Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Office for National Statistics publish annually the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organization, including the Scotland Office, as part of the Civil Service Statistics. This information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank"><strong>https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</strong></a></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-02-06T15:20:10.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681247/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681247/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-01-30","Scotland Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what the level of earnings is of the (a) highest and (b) lowest-paid employees of his Department, its agencies and arms-length bodies; and what the median level of earnings is for such employees.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681248","Scotland Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>I regularly discuss on-going, important issues with the Prime Minster and my Cabinet colleagues.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-02-06T11:10:50.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681248/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681248/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-01-30","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 27 January 2017 to Question 61501, on what date he  last discussed the UK's nuclear deterrent with the (a) Prime Minister and (b) Ministry of Defence; whether missile tests formed part of these discussions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681249","Scotland Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Sewel Convention has been placed on a statutory footing by section 2 of the Scotland Act 2016, which states that the UK Parliament will not normally legislate with regard to devolved matters without consent of the Scottish Parliament. The UK Government’s approach has not changed.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-02-06T11:09:44.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681249/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681249/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681249/answer",,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-01-30","Devolved Matters: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 27 January 2017 to Question 61526, if he will make it his Department's policy to bring forward legislative proposals to prevent the UK Parliament from passing legislation applying to Scotland that makes provision about a devolved matter without the consent of the Scottish Parliament.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681250","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Office for National Statistics publish annually the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organization as part of the Civil Service Statistics. This information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</a></p><p> </p><p>Earning levels for the lowest paid employee are not publically available.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-07T13:20:07.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681250/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681250/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-30","Department for Transport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the level of earnings is of the (a) highest and (b) lowest-paid employees of his Department, its agencies and arms-length bodies; and what the median level of earnings is for such employees.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681251","Wales Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The Office for National Statistics publish annually the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organisation as part of the Civil Service Statistics. This information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</a></p><p> </p><p>Earning levels for the lowest paid employee are not publically available.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-02-06T15:18:11.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681251/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681251/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681251/answer",,,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-01-30","Wales Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what the level of earnings is of the (a) highest and (b) lowest-paid employees of his Department, its agencies and arms-length bodies; and what the median level of earnings is for such employees.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681252","Women and Equalities","false","2017-02-07","<p>As at December 2016 (latest figures available), for staff in the Government Equalities Office (GEO), the level of earnings of the highest and lowest paid employees and the median level of earnings is:</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>GEO Paid staff Dec16 </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Highest Paid</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>*£90,000</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Lowest Paid</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>*£24,380</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Median</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>*£43,740</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>(*Please note these figures are ‘rounded’ to the nearest £5 in line with the Department’s published pay data).</em></p><p> </p><p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent body and makes its own decisions about its staff salaries. I have therefore asked the Chief Executive of the Commission to write to the honourable member responding to the question. I will place a copy of the letter in the libraries of both Houses.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-07T11:50:23.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681252/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681252/answer",,,,,,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-01-30","Government Equalities Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what the level of earnings is of the (a) highest and (b) lowest-paid employees of her Department, its agencies and arms-length bodies; and what the median level of earnings is for such employees.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","62216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681253","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>There will be no public consultation on the proposal to close Edinburgh City Jobcentre as the proposed move to merge with High Riggs Jobcentre is 1.1 miles in distance. We have committed to a public consultation for offices over three miles and 20 minutes away by public transport.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T14:10:46.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681253/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681253/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Edinburgh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether a public consultation will take place on the proposal to close St Andrew Street job centre in Edinburgh.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","62221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681254","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Department has sought, where feasible, to merge sites in close proximity as part of its overall review of estate. Merging the staff and services from Edinburgh City into High Riggs Jobcentre optimises use of space, ensures value for money and enables effective delivery of services to the public. The merge in reverse was explored however this was deemed not viable due to the underutilisation of space.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T14:06:40.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681254/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681254/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Edinburgh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, by what criteria St Andrew Street job centre, Edinburgh, has been selected for closure.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","62222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681255","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>Edinburgh City claimant count is currently shared with High Riggs Jobcentre and primarily split by age group as opposed to postcode.</p><p> </p><p>The claimant count for High Riggs is 2245 of which 720 are female. This information is available from the following link: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk</a>. Figures have been rounded to the nearest 5.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p><p> </p><p>These are UC and JSA claimants served by Edinburgh City and High Riggs Jobcentres. We are unable to identify disabled claimants, or provide exact figures of ESA and IS claimants, however the purpose of the equality analysis is to help establish how many people are likely to be affected by the proposal.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T16:22:55.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681255/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681255/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Edinburgh","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants living in Edinburgh East constituency are served by St Andrew Street job centre, Edinburgh; and how many of those are (a) disabled and (b) women.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","62223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681256","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>We have entered a period of consultation with our staff at Cumnock Killoch House and will be undertaking internal discussions about the options for relocation. It is important to stress that this is a proposal at this stage and we will make a final decision following the consultation process with our colleagues. DWP is retaining a significant presence in Scotland and staff at Cumnock will be offered the opportunity to relocate to other parts of DWP wherever possible.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T14:36:16.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681256/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681256/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: East Ayrshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, where staff based at Cumnock administration centre will be relocated in the event of its closure.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","62183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681257","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>We will be undertaking an equality analysis as part of the detailed planning for service reconfiguration. This will include feedback from public consultation in those locations where this applies. A decision regarding publication of the equality analysis will be made at that time.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T14:34:04.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681257/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681257/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: East Ayrshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he expects to publish an Equality Impact Assessment on the proposal to close Cumnock administration centre.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","62191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681258","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is now consulting with colleagues in Cumnock. We are seeking to relocate, or offer alternative roles, to all employees affected by the proposed closure. It is important to stress that this is a proposed closure: we will make a final decision informed by the consultation with our colleagues. We are not therefore in a position to comment on the potential for redundancy.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T14:30:55.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681258/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681258/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: East Ayrshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will confirm that no compulsory redundancies will result from the closure of Cumnock administration centre.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","62192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681259","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>The overall requirement in DWP for processing work is reducing and we do not need the same size estate we currently have. Specifically, the work undertaken at Cumnock Killoch House is reducing and due to end within the next 2-3 years. The overall requirement for that work from March 2018 is deliverable out of fewer buildings which better match our strategic requirements and therefore the building in Cumnock will no longer be required.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-02T14:21:19.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681259/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681259/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: East Ayrshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, by what criteria Cumnock administration centre was selected for closure.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","62193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681260","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>The available information on the number of foreign nationals registered for National Insurance numbers by geography, including parliamentary constituency and world area is published quarterly and can be found at:<br></p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p>The latest available information is up to September 2016.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-02T14:14:56.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681260/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681260/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","National Insurance: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many nationals of other EU member states registered for national insurance numbers in (a) Greater London and (b) the London Borough of Newham between (i) July and December 2015, (ii) January and June 2016 and (iii) July and December 2016.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","62197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681261","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>It is important to remember that the announcements made in relation to the Written Statement of 26 January 2017 are proposals at this stage and not final decisions. Once a final decision is made, claimants will be informed at an appropriate time prior to any office move.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T11:20:42.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681261/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681261/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people using Cambuslang Jobcentre have been informed in writing of the closure of that jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681262","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>We will be undertaking an equality analysis as part of the detailed planning for service reconfiguration. This will include feedback from public consultation in those locations where this applies.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T10:27:45.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681262/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681262/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681262/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when an equality impact assessment will be published on the proposal to close Cambuslang Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681263","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>We are not yet in a position to share an estimated figure due to commercial confidentiality pending completion of legal processes and staff consultations. We expect to make savings for the tax payer from merging offices by reducing running costs and making best use of office space available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T12:09:30.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681263/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681263/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681263/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the expected costs are of the proposal to relocate staff and resources from Cambuslang Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681264","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>The claimant count for Cambuslang is 410 of which 130 are female. The claimant count for Rutherglen is 465 of which 135 are female. This information is available from the following link: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk</a>. Figures have been rounded to the nearest 5.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These are UC and JSA claimants served by Cambuslang and Rutherglen Jobcentres. We are unable to identify disabled claimants, or provide exact figures of ESA and IS claimants, however the purpose of the equality analysis is to help establish how many people are likely to be affected by the proposal.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T12:29:16.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681264/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681264/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681264/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants are currently served by (a) Cambuslang and (b) Rutherglen Jobcentres; and how many such claimants are (i) disabled and (ii) women.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681265","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>We have carefully considered the wider impacts on local communities when developing our proposals for Cambuslang and Rutherglen jobcentres. The economic impact of employment is dispersed beyond the specific location of a workplace and the staff currently based at Cambuslang jobcentre already live in the broader area around the site. While we expect all these staff to move to Rutherglen jobcentre, it is unlikely that a significant proportion of them will also move their place of residence.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T16:41:40.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681265/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681265/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment has been made of the effect on the local economy of the proposal to relocate jobs from Cambuslang Jobcentre to Rutherglen Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681266","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is now consulting with colleagues at Cambuslang Jobcentre. We are seeking to relocate, or offer alternative roles, to all employees affected by the proposed closure and we anticipate that we will be able to redeploy everyone to Rutherglen Jobcentre.</p><p> </p><p>It is important to stress that this is a proposed closure: we will make a final decision informed by the consultation process with our colleagues. We are not therefore in a position to comment on the potential for redundancy.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T12:33:35.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681266/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681266/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether any compulsory redundancies will result from the closure of Cambuslang Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681267","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Department has sought to merge together multiple sites in close proximity. Merging the staff and services from Cambuslang into Rutherglen Jobcentre maximises use of space and offers good value for money.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T16:17:23.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681267/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681267/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, by what criteria Cambuslang Jobcentre has been selected for closure.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","62173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681268","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Department announced on 30 January our intention to provide around £100m of funding to London and Greater Manchester to develop, procure and deliver localised versions of the new Work and Health Programme to fit the needs of their residents. In addition, the Department has launched a commercial process to let contracts with a total value in excess of £400m for the Work and Health Programme in the rest of England and Wales. We are also in discussion with the Scottish Government about devolving an appropriate level of funding for equivalent support they may wish to offer.</p><p> </p><p>At this point we cannot confirm the financial allocation for each of the next five years as this will be dependent on the outcomes of the commercial process and agreements with HMT on funding beyond the current Spending Review period.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-02-07T10:47:14.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681268/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681268/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Work and Health Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the financial allocation to the Work and Health Programme by his Department will be in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","62146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681269","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>We will be undertaking an equality analysis as part of the detailed planning for the proposed relocation of the medical assessment centre in Ayr.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T10:51:27.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681269/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681269/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681269/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether an equality impact assessment has been undertaken for the proposed relocation of the medical assessment centre from Russell House to Wallacetoun in Ayr.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","62152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681270","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>We are not yet in a position to share an estimated figure due to commercial confidentiality pending completion of legal processes and staff consultations. We expect to make savings for the tax payer from merging offices by reducing running costs and making best use of office space available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T10:59:42.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681270/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681270/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681270/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: East Ayrshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the expected costs are of the proposal to relocate staff and resources from Cumnock administration centre.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","62153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681271","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>We have entered a period of consultation with our staff at Cumnock Killoch House and will be undertaking internal discussions about the options for relocation. It is important to stress that this is a proposal at this stage and we will make a final decision following the consultation process with our colleagues. DWP has a significant presence in Scotland and staff at Cumnock will be offered the opportunity to relocate to other parts of DWP wherever possible.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T16:28:57.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681271/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681271/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681271/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: East Ayrshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment has been made of the effect on the local economy of the proposal to relocate jobs from Cumnock administration centre.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","62154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681272","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-07","<p>A public consultation will not take place on the proposal to close Cumnock Kiloch House, as this is a back of house function and does not affect the services delivered by our jobcentres.</p><p> </p><p>However, we have entered a period of consultation with our staff at Cumnock Kiloch House and will be undertaking internal discussions about the options for relocation. It is important to stress that this is a proposal at this stage and we will make a final decision following the consultation process with our colleagues. DWP is retaining a significant presence in Scotland and staff at Cumnock will be offered the opportunity to relocate to other parts of DWP wherever possible.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-07T16:09:16.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681272/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681272/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681272/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Department for Work and Pensions: East Ayrshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether a public consultation is planned on the proposal to close Cumnock administration centre.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","62155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681273","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-06","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>It is important to bear in mind that Personal Independence Payment is not assessed on the basis of an individual's long term disability or condition based, rather it is based on the needs arising because of the disability or condition.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-02-06T16:22:37.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681273/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681273/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681273/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with conditions that cause short stature have had their mobility payments withdrawn after their transition from disability living allowance to personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for John Nicolson","East Dunbartonshire","John Nicolson","62243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681274","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-02","<p>We continually keep the assessment process for Personal Independence Payment (PIP) and Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) under review.</p><p> </p><p>As announced on 1 October 2016, we will stop requiring people with the most severe, lifetime conditions to be repeatedly assessed for ESA and the Universal Credit equivilant. Over the coming months we will work with our health assessment provider, medical professionals and other stakeholders to develop a set of criteria to switch off re-assessments for people with the most severe health conditions or disabilities.</p><p> </p><p>PIP already recognises that for the most severely disabled claimants, the award review process could seem unnecessarily intrusive. The length of a PIP award is based on an individual’s circumstances and can vary from nine months to an on-going award with a light touch review at the 10 year point. As such, existing PIP claimants with the most severe, lifetime disabilities, whose functional ability has remained the same, are more likely to have their evidence reviewed by a DWP Decision-Maker and will not need to have another face-to-face assessment with a healthcare professional. Regular reviews for PIP claimants are a key feature of the benefit, and ensure that benefit payments accurately match the current needs of claimants.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to engage with stakeholders to improve the service we provide. We are committed to ensuring that the review processes work effectively across the spectrum of disabilities and health conditions.</p><p> </p><p>In addition the Green Paper, launched on 31 October 2016 explores a range of options, and points to long-term reform, including how we might simplify and improve the assessment process.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-02-02T16:34:16.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681274/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681274/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681274/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-30","Work Capability Assessment: Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing a maximum number of face to face assessments for Parkinson's disease sufferers.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","62240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681275","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-07","<p>On average the hourly rate for a cleaning operative is £8.04.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-07T15:24:09.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681275/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681275/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681275/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the hourly pay-rate is for his Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681276","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-07","<p>To date, we have invested £2.57million in the Capital Markets Climate Initiative. This was set up to help us understand the barriers to investment in renewable energy projects in developing countries and facilitate the quick transition of such projects from talk to action, with a particular focus on unlocking flows of private finance. The CMCI programme includes the Global Innovation Lab (the ‘Lab’), which has been endorsed by the Leaders of G7 countries. The Lab has so far catalysed $600million of investments through the instruments it has developed.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-02-07T15:20:38.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681276/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681276/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681276/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much government funding has been invested in the Capital Markets Climate Initiative since the launch of that initiative.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","62251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681277","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Government set out the rationale for moving the Green Investment Bank (GIB) to the private sector in its policy statement “Future of UK Green Investment Bank plc” published on 18 November 2015, including the Government’s assessment of the role GIB has played in unlocking private investment in the green economy. The strong market interest in acquiring a stake in GIB since the sale process was launched on 3 March 2016 further demonstrates the positive impact GIB has had in the market.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-02-07T15:17:09.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681277/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681277/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681277/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","Green Investment Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the contribution of the Minister for Climate Change and Industry of 11 January 2017, Official Report, column 320, what assessment he has made of the nature of the market failure that the Green Investment Bank was set up to rectify; and if he will publish that assessment.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","62145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681278","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Department for Work and Pension’s (DWP) Access to Work scheme provides financial awards to disabled people in order to fund additional support above the level of an employer’s statutory duty to make reasonable adjustments. This supports disabled people to retain work or take up new opportunities, but does not replace employers’ duties under the Equality Act 2010.</p><p>In addition, Disability Confident supports this Government’s commitment to halve the employment gap between disabled and non-disabled people by engaging with employers, who have a crucial role to play in ensuring disabled people are recruited, retained and developed in their careers. The scheme gives employers the opportunity to assess how Disability Confident their business is and sign up at one of three levels. They complete each level before moving on to the next.</p><p>DWP is currently trialling a Small Employer Offer, which provides small employers with a personalised package of support, including adaptations and advice and a payment of £500 after three months when they take on new employees who have a health condition or disability.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-03T11:11:55.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681278/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681278/answer","Stourbridge","Stourbridge","Margot James","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681278/answer/previousversion/33896","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681278/answer/previousversion/33896","Biography information for Margot James","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what financial support his Department has made available in 2016-17 to assist employers supporting disabled people.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","62184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681279","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-02","<p>The industrial strategy green paper, <em>Building our Industrial Strategy</em>, is part of a consultative approach to developing our strategy and seeks views from organisations across the country, including disability organisations. I look forward to further engagement with them, building on engagement with my officials to date.</p><p>The Government is clear that the industrial strategy is part of our work to deliver an economy that works for everyone, including disabled people. In particular, the Government’s green paper <em>Improving Lives – the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper </em>considers how we can improve employment outcomes for disabled people. Many employers are already creating healthy, inclusive workplaces, but more needs to be done so that employers provide the support needed for employees with disabilities and long-term health conditions, to help them get into and stay in work.</p><p>The <em>Improving Lives</em> consultation closes on 17th February, and we will be working to ensure its outcomes are aligned with our industrial strategy.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","62186","2017-02-02T14:48:16.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681279/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681279/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","Industry: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent meetings and discussions he has had with disability organisations on his Department's industrial strategy.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","62185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681280","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-02","<p>The industrial strategy green paper, <em>Building our Industrial Strategy</em>, is part of a consultative approach to developing our strategy and seeks views from organisations across the country, including disability organisations. I look forward to further engagement with them, building on engagement with my officials to date.</p><p>The Government is clear that the industrial strategy is part of our work to deliver an economy that works for everyone, including disabled people. In particular, the Government’s green paper <em>Improving Lives – the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper </em>considers how we can improve employment outcomes for disabled people. Many employers are already creating healthy, inclusive workplaces, but more needs to be done so that employers provide the support needed for employees with disabilities and long-term health conditions, to help them get into and stay in work.</p><p>The <em>Improving Lives</em> consultation closes on 17th February, and we will be working to ensure its outcomes are aligned with our industrial strategy.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","62185","2017-02-02T14:48:16.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681280/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681280/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","Industry: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what provision he has made in his Department's industrial strategy for disabled people.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","62186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681281","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-08","<p>Maintaining the UK’s ability to trade in nuclear materials and equipment will be a key objective in negotiations to allow the uninterrupted progress of the UK’s nuclear programme, which includes the construction of Hinkley Point C. Those negotiations have not yet started, but officials and Ministers are in regular contact with industry stakeholders and will continue to work closely with them as the negotiations progress.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-08T16:36:05.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681281/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681281/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681281/answer/previousversion/33851","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681281/answer/previousversion/33851","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","EURATOM","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of leaving the European Atomic Energy Community on the construction of Hinkley Point C.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","62219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681282","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-20","<p>Withdrawal from the Euratom Treaty will not diminish the UK's nuclear ambitions for its new build nuclear programme, and the Government remains committed to delivering a world leading nuclear programme in close collaboration with international counterparts, including the USA.</p><p>Non EU countries that have a relationship with Euratom do so mainly through international nuclear cooperation agreements (NCA) with the Euratom Community. These provide frameworks for cooperation in the civil nuclear sector, but are not an absolute requirement for trade in civil nuclear material or goods with every country, and in many cases trade continues without being covered by an NCA.</p><p>We will maintain continuity of cooperation and develop new arrangements as necessary.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-20T11:28:32.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681282/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681282/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681282/answer/previousversion/33853","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681282/answer/previousversion/33853","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-30","EURATOM","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of leaving the European Atomic Energy Community on projects that require the co-operation of American nuclear energy companies.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","62220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681283","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>All Government Departments are bound by legal requirements concerning the right to work in the UK and, in addition, the Civil Service Nationality Rules. Evidence of nationality is checked at the point of recruitment into the Civil Service as part of wider pre-employment checks, but there is no requirement on departments to retain this information beyond the point at which it has served its purpose.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-07T17:02:43.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681283/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681283/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","Department for International Trade: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will estimate how many of his Department's staff will be affected by recent changes to immigration rules introduced by President Trump.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","62258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681284","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-07","<p>The Department for International Trade is currently a tenant in other buildings that belong to several other government departments. We do not therefore directly employ cleaners, as the contract is all managed by the property management company for the main landlord.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-07T17:01:25.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681284/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681284/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-30","Department for International Trade: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the hourly pay-rate is for his Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681285","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-07","<p>DExEU is accommodated in Cabinet Office and Ministry of Defence buildings and I refer to the answers given by my honourable friends, the Member for Ipswich (Ben Gummer) on 07 February 2017 and Member for Milton Keynes North (Mark Lancaster) on 02 February 2017.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-07T17:32:38.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681285/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681285/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-30","Department for Exiting the European Union: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the hourly pay-rate is for his Department's cleaning staff.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","62267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681287","Attorney General","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) is the principal prosecuting authority for England and Wales. The functions of the Director of Public Prosecution (DPP) as head of the CPS are set out in section 3 of the Prosecution of Offences Act 1985.</p><p> </p><p>The DPP may instigate a prosecution in any case investigated by the police or any of the Government departments or other agencies specifically set out in section 3 and in the exercise of any power specifically assigned to her by the Attorney General. There is no power to prosecute offences which have been investigated by any person or body not listed in section 3 or in an assignment, with the exception that the DPP may also institute criminal proceedings in any case where it appears to her to be appropriate to do so, including cases of particular importance or difficulty.</p><p> </p><p>The use of this power is rare, and anyone approaching the CPS asking them to consider a case for prosecution under this section will usually be recommended to contact the police, as the CPS has no power to investigate a case.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, section 6 of the same Act preserves the right of any individual to commence a private prosecution although the DPP may also take over such proceedings where it is appropriate.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2017-02-02T18:03:42.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681287/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681287/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681287/answer",,,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-01-30","Crown Prosecution Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what the procedure is for presenting a case to the Crown Prosecution Service independently of the police.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","62297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681288","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>The National Security Council is a Cabinet Committee. Information relating to the proceedings of Cabinet Committees is not disclosed, as to do so could harm the frankness and candour of internal discussion. We do not comment on specifics relating to the National Security Council or national security issues.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-06T10:52:51.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681288/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681288/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-30","National Security Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many meetings of the National Security Council (NSC) have taken place since 13 July 2016; how many of those meetings were chaired by the Prime Minister; and whether there have been any weeks when Parliament has been sitting during that period when the NSC has not met.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","62384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681289","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-02","<p>As the Chancellor outlined at the Treasury Select Committee, the government is carrying out both national and regional analysis of leaving the European Union, which will help to inform the Prime Minister’s negotiating strategy.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-02-02T15:58:05.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681289/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681289/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-30","Economic Situation: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the potential effect on the economy of (a) Nottingham and (b) the East Midlands of the UK leaving the EU and reverting to World Trade Organisation rules.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","62381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681290","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-02","<p>The NAO report published in November 2016 shows the amount of compliance yield collected by the High Net Worth Unit in HM Revenue and Customs over the last five years. This was:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Yield</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£200 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£223 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£268 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£414 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£416 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>In this period the High Net Worth Unit has increased the yield from its work each year and exceeded the annual yield targets that it agreed internally.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-02T16:51:11.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681290/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681290/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-30","High Net Worth Unit: Tax Yields","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of trends in the revenue collected by HM Revenue and Customs High Net Worth Unit in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","62293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681291","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-06","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have put in place a £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme for England to support ratepayers at the 2017 revaluation. As part of the consultation on the transitional relief scheme my Department published analysis of the impact of the revaluation by sector and region.</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/business-rates-revaluation-2017" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/consultations/business-rates-revaluation-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>As regards the approach to valuing pubs, an Approved Guide for the Valuation of Public Houses for business rates has been agreed between the Valuation Office Agency and all 5 bodies representing pubs including the British Beer and Pub Association and the Association of Licensed Multiple Retailers.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","62287","2017-02-06T17:39:47.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681291/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681291/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-30","Licensed Premises: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department plans to review the current level of business rates for licensed premises.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","62283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681292","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-06","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have put in place a £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme for England to support ratepayers at the 2017 revaluation. As part of the consultation on the transitional relief scheme my Department published analysis of the impact of the revaluation by sector and region.</p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/business-rates-revaluation-2017" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/consultations/business-rates-revaluation-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>As regards the approach to valuing pubs, an Approved Guide for the Valuation of Public Houses for business rates has been agreed between the Valuation Office Agency and all 5 bodies representing pubs including the British Beer and Pub Association and the Association of Licensed Multiple Retailers.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","62283","2017-02-06T17:39:47.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681292/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681292/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-30","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on different sectors of business of different business rates being in effect in different parts of the UK.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","62287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681293","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-02-07","<p>My Rt Hon Friend, the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government has made clear he will be studying Dame Louise Casey’s Review of integration and opportunity closely.</p><p>As part of those considerations, we will consider carefully Dame Louise’s recommendation that British values be included in a new oath for those in public office. The Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, published an editorial in the Sunday Times (18th December), in which he noted that he was ‘particularly drawn’ to this recommendation.</p><p>The Government will bring forward a new Integration Strategy in the Spring.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-02-07T16:10:26.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681293/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/681293/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-30","National Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress has been made on his proposals to introduce a British Values Oath.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","62387"
